  "lessons": [
    {
      "key": "Pre-Assessment",
      "name": "Pre-Assessment",
      "absolute_position": 1,
      "lockable": true,
      "has_lesson_plan": false,
      "relative_position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "assessment": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Pre-Assessment",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "aif2-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Computing Careers",
      "name": "Lesson 1: Computing Careers",
      "absolute_position": 2,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-user-graduate\"></i> ***Career Journeys***\n\n**How do your skills and interests align with computing careers and emerging technologies?**\n\nIn this lesson, students explore how their skills and interests align with computing careers and emerging technologies. Through collaborative activities, they analyze career personas, connect traits to career categories, and identify technologies that enhance career opportunities. At the end of the lesson, students reflect on their own traits and how they align with potential computing careers.",
        "preparation": "- Provide copies of the Vision Board template (one for each pair of students)\n- Ensure students have access to their Unit Guides (print copies or provide digital copies)\n- Complete the Unit Guide Key in advance with your own interests and skills",
        "student_overview": "**How do your skills and interests align with computing careers and emerging technologies?**\n\nExplore how your skills and interests connect to exciting computing careers and technologies. Discover how emerging technologies solve real-world problems and reflect on the skills you have that align with your future goals."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Computing Careers",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "aif2-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Computational Thinking",
      "name": "Lesson 2: Computational Thinking",
      "absolute_position": 3,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can computational thinking help us simplify and solve complex problems?**\n\nIn this lesson, students activate prior knowledge about breaking tasks into smaller steps and practice computational thinking as a structured problem solving approach. They work in pairs to plan a school event (e.g., fundraiser, dance, talent show), applying computational thinking pillars (decomposition and abstraction) to solve the challenge. Students have an opportunity to use an AI Chatbot to help them complete the activity guide. During the wrap up, students reflect on the activity they completed and discuss the computational skills they practiced.",
        "preparation": "- Print copies and cut up sets of Baking a Cake cards (one for each pair of students)\n- Decide how you want students to complete the Planning a School Event activity and then accordingly complete one or more of the following:\n     - Print copies of the Planning a School Event activity guide (one for each pair of students)\n     - Gather several sticky notes for each student\n     - Distribute copies of the Digital Manipulative Support version of the Activity Guide",
        "student_overview": "**How can computational thinking help us simplify and solve complex problems?**\n\nApply computational thinking principles —decomposition and abstraction — to plan a school event, and use an AI Chatbot for support."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Computational Thinking",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "aif2-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Designing Algorithms",
      "name": "Lesson 3: Designing Algorithms",
      "absolute_position": 4,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can we design algorithms to make decisions fairly and effectively?**\n\nIn this lesson, students explore the process of designing algorithms, breaking them into manageable steps, and visualizing them as flowcharts. They learn to incorporate sequencing, selection, and iteration into their algorithms and connect their work to real-world applications of AI, such as content moderation. Students also engage in peer feedback to refine their designs and reflect on ethical implications of algorithmic decision-making.",
        "preparation": "- Decide how you want students to complete the Designing Algorithm activity and then accordingly complete one or more of the following:\n   - Prepare sticky notes in two colors for each pair of students\n   - Distribute copies of the Digital Manipulative Support - Flowchart Template",
        "student_overview": "**How can we design algorithms to make decisions fairly and effectively?**\n\nLearn how to create and refine algorithms to solve real-world problems. Explore how algorithms make decisions using sequencing, selection, and iteration, and connect your learning to how AI moderates content."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Designing Algorithms",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "aif2-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Variables and Data Flow",
      "name": "Lesson 4: Variables and Data Flow",
      "absolute_position": 5,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How do programs use variables to store and update information as they run?**\n\nIn this lesson, students explore how programs use variables to store and update information while they run. After brainstorming different types of data apps might need to remember, students are introduced to Python and learn how to create, modify, and print variables of different data types. Through short, hands-on coding activities, students practice using arithmetic operations, identifying type compatibility, and debugging simple syntax errors.",
        "student_overview": "**How do programs use variables to store and update information as they run?**\n\nIn this lesson, you learn how to use variables to help programs remember and update information, just like real apps do. You write your first Python code, create and change variables, and explore how different types of data—like numbers, text, and true/false values—work in a program. You also practice fixing bugs, using operations like `+` and `-`, and printing results to see how your code works. By the end of the lesson, you build a short program that uses your own variables and reflects something you care about."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Variables and Data Flow",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "aif2-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Working with Objects",
      "name": "Lesson 5: Working with Objects",
      "absolute_position": 6,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How do programmers use objects to organize and control the behavior of things in a program?**\n\nIn this lesson, students are introduced to objects in Python by working with a pre-built `Painter` class. They learn to create an object, use dot notation to call methods like `move()` and `turn_left()`, and apply the UMPIRE strategy to plan, program, and debug a short sequence of instructions. Through hands-on coding challenges in The Neighborhood environment, students build foundational skills in object-oriented thinking, syntax, and sequencing.",
        "student_overview": "**How do programmers use objects to organize and control the behavior of things in a program?**\n\nIn this lesson, you learn how to control a `Painter` object using code. You use commands like `move()` and `turn_left()` to help the `Painter` navigate a grid, and practice writing, predicting, and debugging short programs. The UMPIRE strategy helps you plan and improve your code. By the end of the lesson, you understand how objects work in Python and how programmers give them instructions using dot notation."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Working with Objects",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "aif2-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Functions",
      "name": "Lesson 6: Functions",
      "absolute_position": 7,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can writing your own functions help you solve problems more efficiently in your code?**\n\nIn this lesson, students explore how functions can help simplify and organize code. They begin with an unplugged activity where they create and name a sequence of steps, then connect this to function definitions and calls in Python. Through a series of short practice and challenge levels, students define and call functions, replace repeated code with function calls, and debug function-related errors. By the end of the lesson, students understand how functions support abstraction, reusability, and efficient problem-solving in programs.",
        "preparation": "- Print copies of the Function Template (one for each group of 3-4 students)\n- Print copies of the Instruction Cards (one deck for each group of 3-4 students)\n- (Optional) Cut out the Instruction Cards and place in baggies",
        "student_overview": "**How can writing your own functions help you solve problems more efficiently in your code?**\n\nIn this lesson, you learn how to make your code easier to read and reuse by writing your own functions. You start by creating a sequence of steps and giving it a name, just like in programming. Then, you define and call functions in Python, fix common mistakes, and use the UMPIRE strategy to plan and debug your code."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Functions",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "aif2-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Functions with Parameters",
      "name": "Lesson 7: Functions with Parameters",
      "absolute_position": 8,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can adding a parameter to a function make your code more powerful and reusable?**\n\nIn this lesson, students learn how parameters make functions more powerful and reusable by writing, modifying, and debugging functions that take arguments. Through a mix of unplugged discussions, coding challenges, and structured practice in Python Lab, students explore the difference between parameters and arguments, practice writing custom helper functions in a separate file (`custom.py`), and call them from their main program using `from custom import`. Students also begin using the Backpack to save and reuse code, and apply the UMPIRE strategy to structure their thinking when writing functions.",
        "student_overview": "**How can adding a parameter to a function make your code more powerful and reusable?**\n\nIn this lesson, you explore how to make your functions more flexible using parameters. You use arguments to customize what your code does, write and organize helper functions in `custom.py`, and solve creative challenges in the Neighborhood. You practice using the UMPIRE strategy to plan your functions, and learn how to save your work to the Backpack so you can reuse it later."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Functions with Parameters",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "aif2-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Introduction to Loops",
      "name": "Lesson 8: Introduction to Loops",
      "absolute_position": 9,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can we use loops to make our code repeat instructions and solve problems more efficiently?**\n\nIn this lesson, students are introduced to `while` loops as a way to repeat instructions in Python while a condition remains true. The lesson begins with an unplugged activity to help students intuitively understand repetition and stopping conditions, then transitions into guided practice with loop syntax and structure. Through scaffolded levels, students modify, debug, and write `while` loops using conditions like `can_move()` and `has_paint()`, with increasing independence and creativity.",
        "student_overview": "**How can we use loops to make our code repeat instructions and solve problems more efficiently?**\n\nIn this lesson, you get to explore how to make your code repeat steps without copying the same line over and over. You'll try out `while` loops in Python and see how they can help the `Painter` keep moving, paint a path, or stop when something changes. Along the way, you fix loops that don't work, write your own functions, and use conditions like `can_move()` and `has_paint()` to decide when a loop should stop."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Introduction to Loops",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "aif2-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Conditional Statements",
      "name": "Lesson 9: Conditional Statements",
      "absolute_position": 10,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can we use conditional statements to help a computer make decisions?**\n\nIn this lesson, students are introduced to conditional statements and how they help programs make decisions. The lesson begins with an unplugged activity to activate prior knowledge about conditions and selection, followed by a guided introduction to the structure and syntax of `if` statements in Python. Students explore simple conditionals and then apply their understanding, including debugging, direction-based decisions, and using `if` statements inside `while` loops.",
        "student_overview": "**How can we use conditional statements to help a computer make decisions?**\n\nIn this lesson, you learn how to use conditional statements to help programs make decisions. The lesson starts with a real-world activity to explore how conditions work, then moves into writing `if` statements in Python to control what a program does based on different situations. You practice using conditionals with the `Painter` to solve challenges, fix bugs, and make the `Painter` respond to what's happening in its environment."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Conditional Statements",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "aif2-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Algorithms IRL",
      "name": "Lesson 10: Algorithms IRL",
      "absolute_position": 11,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How might algorithms impact our daily lives?**\n\nThis lesson explores how algorithms make decisions in real-world applications and the ethical challenges that arise from those decisions. Students analyze and debug a flawed music recommendation algorithm, then examine the ethical trade-offs in autonomous vehicle decision-making. Through discussion and reflection, students consider how fairness, bias, and transparency impact trust in algorithmic systems.",
        "preparation": "- Print copies of the Algorithm Decision-Making activity guide (one per pair of students)",
        "student_overview": "**How might algorithms impact our daily lives?**\n\nAlgorithms make decisions in apps and technology, affecting everything from music recommendations to self-driving cars. In this lesson, explore how algorithms work, identify their limitations, and consider the ethical challenges of making fair and trustworthy decisions."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Algorithms IRL",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "aif2-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Decomposition",
      "name": "Lesson 11: Decomposition",
      "absolute_position": 12,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**What skills or characteristics helped you decompose your code to be more efficient today?**\n\nIn this lesson, students strengthen their understanding of decomposition by reflecting on past applications and working in small groups to break down a pixel image into functions using Python pseudocode. They then transition to coding their image through pair programming, testing, and debugging. The lesson concludes with a reflection on the importance of decomposition in solving complex problems efficiently.",
        "preparation": "- Print copies of the Decomposing a Pixel Image activity guide (one per pair of students)",
        "student_overview": "**What skills or characteristics helped you decompose your code to be more efficient today?**\n\nBreak down a pixel image into functions using pseudocode, then code it in Python. Reflect on how decomposition makes problem-solving more efficient."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Decomposition",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "aif2-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Two-Way and Nested Selection",
      "name": "Lesson 12: Two-Way Selection",
      "absolute_position": 13,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can a program make a choice between two different outcomes, and when should it use `if` versus `if/else`?**\n\nIn this lesson, students deepen their understanding of conditional logic by learning how to use `if/else` statements to write programs that make decisions between two outcomes. Building on their prior experience with one-way selection (`if`), students compare the two structures, explore when each is appropriate, and write `if/else` statements in increasingly complex contexts—including within loops. Through scaffolded programming tasks in The Neighborhood, students modify, debug, and write original code that uses two-way selection to control behavior. By the end of the lesson, they are able to identify situations where two different actions are needed and structure their code to handle both paths effectively.",
        "student_overview": "**How can a program make a choice between two different outcomes, and when should it use `if` versus `if/else`?**\n\nThis lesson introduces how to use `if/else` statements to help a program choose between two different actions. By exploring programs that use only `if` and comparing them to ones that use `if/else`, you get to see how two-way decisions work in real code. In The Neighborhood, the `Painter` follows paths, picks up paint, and reacts to obstacles based on conditions you write using `if/else`."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Two-Way and Nested Selection",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "aif2-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Pixels of Me Project",
      "name": "Lesson 13: Pixels of Me Project",
      "absolute_position": 14,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "assessment": true,
        "overview": "**How can I represent something about myself using programming and art?**\n\nIn this project, students design and code a pixel image that represents some aspect of them. They use computational thinking to break their design into subtasks, such as defining functions, coding loops, and using selection statements. They can use AI for brainstorming and debugging and then further refine their ideas through peer feedback and reflection. The project culminates in a gallery walk in which students show off their work.",
        "preparation": "- Print copies of the Pixels of Me Project Planning Guide (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "**How can I represent something about myself using programming and art?**\n\nUse Python to code a pixel image that represents. Apply your computational thinking skills to design, refine, and showcase your work."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Pixels of Me Project",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-4",
        "script.name": "aif2-2025"
      }
    },
