      "key": "bdebef46-2c4b-49c5-b9d8-0ff764c98fe7",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson_activity.key": "bdebef46-2c4b-49c5-b9d8-0ff764c98fe7",
        "lesson.key": "Two-Way and Nested Selection (Lesson 12)",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-6",
        "script.name": "aif2-2025"
      }
    }
  ],
  "activity_sections": [
    {
      "key": "f852ecf9-10e0-42ee-b61c-c7c80919f4ea",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Pre-Assessment"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f852ecf9-10e0-42ee-b61c-c7c80919f4ea",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3bd28f0c-6c51-4457-ab91-022c965df637"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "15981b4a-9de1-4353-a29b-7eff4b689e9c",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Today, we’re kicking off with a few quick choices to get you thinking about how technology and computing shape the tools you use every day. I’ll show you two options — pick the one you would rather use or do! There are no wrong answers — just your personal preference.\n\n",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "15981b4a-9de1-4353-a29b-7eff4b689e9c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ed8ddd9f-750a-41bb-8edb-0741717e4d4d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5d1a82d9-3ea0-4c93-8f7f-c85aaed0a835",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n\n- *Create short videos (TikTok/Reels) or stream live (Twitch/YouTube Live)?*\n- *Invent a new app or improve how an existing app works?*\n- *Work with people or work with data?*\n\nUse Think-Pair-Share to facilitate a rapid discussion and share out after each pair of options.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Highlight how computing skills and emerging technologies contribute to everyday tools and innovations students enjoy."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5d1a82d9-3ea0-4c93-8f7f-c85aaed0a835",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ed8ddd9f-750a-41bb-8edb-0741717e4d4d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "51eed653-117b-4ec6-8ccc-c3a0a135039f",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Foundations of AI Programming Unit Guide.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students will be using this every lesson throughout the unit. We highly recommend distributing physical copies of the Unit Guide for this unit to allow students to annotate code snippets. If you choose to have students make their own digital copies, you will need to provide guidance to students when annotating code since these code snippets are Drawings inserted into the documents.  \n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "51eed653-117b-4ec6-8ccc-c3a0a135039f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ed8ddd9f-750a-41bb-8edb-0741717e4d4d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d2f1e7ae-bbdc-4b90-8063-15ff6d9f87aa",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define **emerging technology** and explain some examples of emerging technologies, such as AI and Generative AI, robotics, the Internet of Things, Quantum Computing, augmented reality and virtual reality, and automation.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students are provided with a space to record important vocabulary in their Unit Guides. However, you might choose to also keep track of vocab words in a central place in the classroom, such as a Word Wall or Anchor Chart. See the Guide to Teaching Vocabulary to pick the instructional tool, resources, engagement and practice that works best for you and your students. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d2f1e7ae-bbdc-4b90-8063-15ff6d9f87aa",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ed8ddd9f-750a-41bb-8edb-0741717e4d4d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "26aa6d30-09bb-48b8-ac5f-3f2ba27a2422",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "26aa6d30-09bb-48b8-ac5f-3f2ba27a2422",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ed8ddd9f-750a-41bb-8edb-0741717e4d4d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f4d99dc6-18c0-444a-bf42-d6bed8fb6dfa",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What are some ways that emerging technologies might be involved with things you do everyday?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Highlight the connection between emerging technologies and real-world things that they use everyday. Guide students to see that technology plays a role in creating and improving everyday things that they already use. For example, if a student says they love TikTok, you could connect it to a person working in software development (creating the app) and using AI (personalized recommendations). If a student mentions books, you could connect how robotics or automation could be used to make and ship the books or computer vision could be used to take inventory. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Allow students to take a minute to brainstorm with their partner some ways that emerging technologies might be involved in things you do everyday. Then facilitate a quick discussion, collecting a few examples and connecting them to a type of computing job or computing skills and emerging technologies. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f4d99dc6-18c0-444a-bf42-d6bed8fb6dfa",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ed8ddd9f-750a-41bb-8edb-0741717e4d4d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "781761a0-d42e-443c-8fe9-7b72ba8c184a",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "781761a0-d42e-443c-8fe9-7b72ba8c184a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ed8ddd9f-750a-41bb-8edb-0741717e4d4d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8150112e-fc98-4d05-aaa9-570db5744186",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the learning objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8150112e-fc98-4d05-aaa9-570db5744186",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ed8ddd9f-750a-41bb-8edb-0741717e4d4d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2dd0ed44-a3ed-4a6a-b3a9-84f9ab354a65",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to complete the My Interests and Skills section of their Unit Guide.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "My Skills and Interests",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Complete the Unit Guide Key in advance with your own interests and skills so you can show students an example of how they should fill out their Unit Guide. \n\nNote: It will be easier for students to copy and paste their responses in Level 1 if they work on their Unit Guide digitally.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2dd0ed44-a3ed-4a6a-b3a9-84f9ab354a65",
        "lesson_activity.key": "dfb7c878-3cc0-44d0-b416-89e2e604b4fb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "692b3fd7-1244-4413-a1f8-bb0a9c822d16",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Open the Teacher Key for the Unit Guide, then go to Code Studio and open Level 1. Demo for students how to copy and paste answers from their Unit Guide into AI Chat. Have a few back and forth interactions with the chatbot before prompting it with the following: “Based on what I've shared, would you recommend I explore careers related to People, Things, or Ideas? Explain why.”",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Complete the key in advance with your own interests and skills. Show students how the AI Chatbot will have a personalized conversation with you based on what you wrote. You might also call on a few students to share their interests with the chatbot to encourage more active student engagement."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "692b3fd7-1244-4413-a1f8-bb0a9c822d16",
        "lesson_activity.key": "dfb7c878-3cc0-44d0-b416-89e2e604b4fb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "31cb443d-0869-41be-b2d7-2832f85fc5bd",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** \nBefore students start working, explain that careers can often be grouped based on the kind of work involved: working with People, working with Ideas, or working with Things. Explain to students that they'll work with AI Chat to make connections between their skills and different computing careers.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 1, Level 1. Have students copy and paste (or type out) their responses to the My Interests and Skills section of their unit guide into AI Chat. Have students go back and forth with AI Chat several times to give it key background information. \n",
        "progression_name": "My Skills and Interests"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "31cb443d-0869-41be-b2d7-2832f85fc5bd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "dfb7c878-3cc0-44d0-b416-89e2e604b4fb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f0b319ff-a711-4ae9-b7b8-02cf6f7fb5af",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f0b319ff-a711-4ae9-b7b8-02cf6f7fb5af",
        "lesson_activity.key": "dfb7c878-3cc0-44d0-b416-89e2e604b4fb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6fced135-358d-4aa5-9e84-24be43206f2a",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Look for students struggling to provide sufficient information about their skills and interests. Ask students probing questions such as, \"What activities do you do after school?\" or \"What are your favorite subjects in school?\" As you walk around the room, ensure students are giving AI Chat enough context for it to choose a career category.\n\n\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Remind students that they should not give AI Chat any personally identifying information. For example, they can share that they are in the high school chorus, but should not share the name of their school.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6fced135-358d-4aa5-9e84-24be43206f2a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "dfb7c878-3cc0-44d0-b416-89e2e604b4fb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7fe05c39-b4d9-432c-853d-2ce680a1a591",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** As a quick assessment, ask students to raise their hands based on what category AI Chat suggested. “For example, raise your hand if AI Chat suggested you focus on people-oriented careers.” Explain to students that they'll use these categories throughout the next activity to explore different computing careers and make connections to necessary skills and technologies.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have each student make a copy of the Vision Board template. Explain that students will complete the first column, My Interests and Skills. As they look through Level 2, students should start thinking about careers they can add to the middle column.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Career Exploration",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students will be adding to their vision boards throughout the lesson. The template is formatted as a table for students to add in bullet points, however depending on time you might encourage students to add images, videos, or links.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7fe05c39-b4d9-432c-853d-2ce680a1a591",
        "lesson_activity.key": "dfb7c878-3cc0-44d0-b416-89e2e604b4fb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "de33a9df-3f9b-4a23-a6d0-a14aa7d423da",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 1, Level 2 to choose the suggested career category suggested in the previous level. Students will look at the different careers and add one or two that interests them to the Future Careers column of their vision board.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Some students may have gotten more than one career category suggestion from AI Chat. Encourage students to look over the different levels but focus on two careers for their vision board."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "de33a9df-3f9b-4a23-a6d0-a14aa7d423da",
        "lesson_activity.key": "dfb7c878-3cc0-44d0-b416-89e2e604b4fb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "072230f9-385e-456c-b83a-2c3efae2f398",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Career Exploration"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "072230f9-385e-456c-b83a-2c3efae2f398",
        "lesson_activity.key": "dfb7c878-3cc0-44d0-b416-89e2e604b4fb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b7ca5133-3284-4c5e-8ebf-3054157977fc",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now that you’ve explored a few careers that align with your skills and interests, it’s time to start building your vision board. This will help you organize your thinking and connect what you're good at with careers you might want to explore further.\n\n",
        "name": "Designing My Vision Board",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b7ca5133-3284-4c5e-8ebf-3054157977fc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "dfb7c878-3cc0-44d0-b416-89e2e604b4fb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "70a273fd-5138-4de0-a402-ac050c8e296f",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to begin creating their vision board by completing the first two columns. In Column 1, they should reflect on their interests and strengths, using examples from earlier discussions or their Unit Guide. In Column 2, they’ll add 1–2 careers they found intriguing in Level 2, making sure to include key details or visuals that explain why those careers stood out. Remind students that they’re building something they’ll use in the next step, so they should put effort into making it informative and personal before downloading it as an image.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Look for students who are including personal touches in Column 1 (e.g., hobbies, school subjects, strengths). For Column 2, encourage students to add not just job titles, but what caught their attention about the careers — such as salary ranges, tools used, or tasks performed.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students finish early, encourage them to add icons, logos, or visuals from their research to make their vision board more engaging and unique to them.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "70a273fd-5138-4de0-a402-ac050c8e296f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "dfb7c878-3cc0-44d0-b416-89e2e604b4fb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "475adf23-042e-4c50-8b2b-433aa4695929",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 1, Level 3 to collaborate with AI to get suggestions about emerging technology that align with students’ interests, skills, and career choices. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Listen for how students are prompting AI. If responses feel generic, ask: “Can you be more specific about what you’re interested in?” or “What would you like to know about how this tech is used?”",
        "name": "Emerging Technologies",
        "progression_name": "Envisioning My Future",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Reinforce digital safety—students should not include their real names or personal information when sharing their vision board image. Before students upload, remind them to double-check their file and chat messages to make sure no personal details are included.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "475adf23-042e-4c50-8b2b-433aa4695929",
        "lesson_activity.key": "dfb7c878-3cc0-44d0-b416-89e2e604b4fb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6e7b7d67-ecb6-41e6-8650-34562471bb0c",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to use the AI suggestions as a springboard to explore technologies they might want to learn more about. Instruct them to complete the final column of their vision board with any emerging technologies they found exciting, relevant, or surprising. They can include descriptions, visuals, or links to support their choices. If time allows, invite students to share their vision boards with a partner or small group.\n\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Look for students who are thoughtfully connecting the AI suggestions to their existing interests or skills. Ask questions like: “Which tech seems like a good fit for your strengths or passions?” or \t“Can you see yourself using or building this tech in the future?” Support students who are unsure by helping them revisit earlier parts of their board or offering a few AI suggestions for inspiration. Encourage them to explain their choices — not just list a technology — and to make their boards visually engaging and personally meaningful.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If time permits, consider organizing a gallery walk or peer share so students can showcase their completed vision boards. This builds community and helps students see the variety of tech-career connections.\n"
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "Students’ completed vision boards can be used to assess their understanding of how personal interests connect to computing careers and emerging technologies. Look for evidence that students have made thoughtful connections between their skills and the AI-recommended tech, and that they can explain why those connections matter.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6e7b7d67-ecb6-41e6-8650-34562471bb0c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "dfb7c878-3cc0-44d0-b416-89e2e604b4fb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "214841b5-2893-4086-a1a7-70c2bb26a5d4",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "214841b5-2893-4086-a1a7-70c2bb26a5d4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "dfb7c878-3cc0-44d0-b416-89e2e604b4fb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b176f1d9-720a-43f8-8914-9001c5ee6140",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Read the question aloud and let students know this is their chance to reflect on the connections they've made throughout the lesson. Then show the next slide for extra guidance.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Rephrase the question using the breakdown on the slide and in their Unit Guide to help students think more specifically. Direct them to write their answer in the Question of the Day section of Lesson 1 in their Unit Guide. If students are stuck, prompt them to refer to their vision board for inspiration.\n\n\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Look for students who might be unsure of their response and provide guidance: \"Think about a skill or interest you rated yourself highly on earlier. How did it connect to one of the careers we explored?\"",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If time allows, end the wrap-up with a whole-class share-out: Ask students if anyone would like to share a connection they made between their skills, a computing career, and an emerging technology? This can help reinforce key takeaways and provide inspiration for students who may have struggled.\n"
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The question of the day in the Unit Guide can be used to assess the lesson objectives.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b176f1d9-720a-43f8-8914-9001c5ee6140",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f066a060-a428-405d-a6a3-fd9a52b4f9b6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6841dd72-3c07-4971-bbd9-d8b7494590ac",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6841dd72-3c07-4971-bbd9-d8b7494590ac",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f066a060-a428-405d-a6a3-fd9a52b4f9b6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "11519843-c123-4665-96e8-8ebccff5c41c",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Student Survey"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "11519843-c123-4665-96e8-8ebccff5c41c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f066a060-a428-405d-a6a3-fd9a52b4f9b6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ad98f01c-e591-483b-a1ce-708ddd8f0cea",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Place students in pairs or small groups of three.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair of students a set of the Baking a Cake cards.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "You also have the option to have students complete this matching activity digitally using the Baking Cake Cards Google Slides. This single resource can be used as-is on a device or printed and cut out for hands-on use."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ad98f01c-e591-483b-a1ce-708ddd8f0cea",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9ccfa017-dd35-4bd3-b1a5-b029d6c4b4d6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7b72f8cc-8a05-42bd-b7aa-9e3d993c1292",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": " Don’t worry about getting this “right” — just focus on what makes sense to you. In a few minutes, we’ll give you the official names for these groups, but first we want to see how you think about organizing these ideas.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7b72f8cc-8a05-42bd-b7aa-9e3d993c1292",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9ccfa017-dd35-4bd3-b1a5-b029d6c4b4d6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3b6e0c69-eb76-43e0-92fb-8ea88e65c02e",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students group the cards by the kind of task they represent — even if they don’t know the formal terms yet. They should focus on what the card is doing: Is it describing a step? Repeating something? Leaving out extra details?\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Have students take out their Programming Fundamentals Unit Guide.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3b6e0c69-eb76-43e0-92fb-8ea88e65c02e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9ccfa017-dd35-4bd3-b1a5-b029d6c4b4d6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "53df3809-bd35-409a-9c00-05619fe7b2dd",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Great work! You just used four powerful ways of thinking to organize a real-world task — even if you didn’t know it yet. These are the building blocks of something called computational thinking, and today we’re going to dive into two of them: decomposition and abstraction.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "53df3809-bd35-409a-9c00-05619fe7b2dd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9ccfa017-dd35-4bd3-b1a5-b029d6c4b4d6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5829464a-b671-42f9-bb67-d61bb90963c4",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *computational thinking*. Explain that computational thinking is like cooking a recipe:\n- You break down the recipe into steps – prepping ingredients, cooking, plating.\n- You notice similarities with other recipes you've made – chopping vegetables, boiling water.\n- You focus on essential steps and ignore unnecessary details – you don't need to know how the oven works, just how to set the temperature.\n- You follow or create a step-by-step process to cook the dish.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain that computational thinking consists of four pillars: decomposition, pattern recognition, abstraction, and algorithm design. Emphasize that computational thinking isn't just for coding – these pillars are useful for solving all kinds of real-world problems.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "This lesson will focus on decomposition and abstraction only, and pattern recognition and algorithm design will be discussed in greater depth in upcoming lessons, so don't spend too much time explaining all four of these pillars now."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5829464a-b671-42f9-bb67-d61bb90963c4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9ccfa017-dd35-4bd3-b1a5-b029d6c4b4d6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "de9e4af1-e992-4574-9742-b23078cd7ea7",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the learning objectives.\n\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "de9e4af1-e992-4574-9742-b23078cd7ea7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9ccfa017-dd35-4bd3-b1a5-b029d6c4b4d6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4b94bf26-d09a-4124-9122-b15885be3500",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Today you are going to be asked to solve a problem. We’ll be using a well-known strategy called UMPIRE to help us work through this task. As we go through the UMPIRE strategy, we’ll be using computational thinking to help us go through these steps. ",
        "name": "School Event Planning Challenge",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4b94bf26-d09a-4124-9122-b15885be3500",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c32b75a0-affb-4678-a22e-3b53a7c1985a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "40d0bb52-111c-43a9-9cd6-92ae2415d410",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce students to the UMPIRE strategy, which helps organize their thinking while solving coding problems. Have students follow along in their Unit Guides as you briefly explain each step:\n- **Understand:** State the problem or task\n- **Make a Plan:** Create a flowchart, mind map, pseudocode, or a general brainstorm of ideas. Use computational thinking to help clarify your approach. \n- **Produce:* Create a prototype or rough draft.\n- **Inspect:** Share your ideas with others and learn about their solutions.\n- **Refine:** Iterate on your solution.\n- **Explain:** Reflect on your output, your choices, or your process.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "40d0bb52-111c-43a9-9cd6-92ae2415d410",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c32b75a0-affb-4678-a22e-3b53a7c1985a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3d5ce63f-9fb8-4e18-a6f4-36e646089bc7",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Place students in pairs or small groups of three.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair of students a copy of the Planning a School Event activity guide.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Optionally, you can also give each pair a several sticky notes for them to write down their task ideas or provide them with the Digital Manipulative Support version of the activity guide linked in the Resources section of this lesson plan. This will make the process of refining their ideas easier than having to revise them directly on the activity guide.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3d5ce63f-9fb8-4e18-a6f4-36e646089bc7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c32b75a0-affb-4678-a22e-3b53a7c1985a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2592c796-cceb-4fb6-b00e-c385e430a96b",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that students will work with their partner to plan a school event (e.g., fundraiser, dance, talent show). Allow students to either select from a provided list or come up with their own school or community-related event and describe their event in their activity guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *decomposition*."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2592c796-cceb-4fb6-b00e-c385e430a96b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c32b75a0-affb-4678-a22e-3b53a7c1985a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c75e44e4-3ee0-4847-883f-d4f42c7a2aff",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "When you start a jigsaw puzzle, you don't try to put everything together at once. Instead, you break it down into smaller steps – first sorting edge pieces, then grouping by colors or patterns, and finally assembling sections before putting everything together.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c75e44e4-3ee0-4847-883f-d4f42c7a2aff",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c32b75a0-affb-4678-a22e-3b53a7c1985a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "add1e159-a85e-412e-a612-0e78b40d263e",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "add1e159-a85e-412e-a612-0e78b40d263e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c32b75a0-affb-4678-a22e-3b53a7c1985a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cae3332b-8709-40c7-8436-e0f69d4dcdce",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 2 Level 1. Students will use the AI chatbot to assist with completing the Decomposition section of the Planning a School Event activity guide.",
        "progression_name": "Decomposition"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cae3332b-8709-40c7-8436-e0f69d4dcdce",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c32b75a0-affb-4678-a22e-3b53a7c1985a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5002d390-eaf8-4fd5-8704-0026f3c63602",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Walk around and observe students as they work on their activity guide. Ask guiding questions like, \"What’s something you would need to buy for this type of event?\" and \"What types of tasks are similar to each other?\"",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Before students start filling out the activity guide, consider demonstrating how to use a chatbot level. Copy and paste one of the prompts from the activity guide into the first AI chatbot. Show students how they can customize the prompt to fit their needs and ask follow up questions to get the best responses. Encourage students to use the Tips at the bottom of the instruction panel. Demonstrate how to copy and paste one of the suggestions (e.g. \"Come up with 3 more ideas\") into the chat box after initiating a dialogue with the chatbot.\n\nStudents may have varying degrees of success with the example prompts, depending on the type of event they chose and the task they need clarified. Encourage students to customize these prompts to get the output they need. Highlight any pairs who have found particularly effective system prompts and encourage other students to use the same prompt template."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5002d390-eaf8-4fd5-8704-0026f3c63602",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c32b75a0-affb-4678-a22e-3b53a7c1985a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "acd669ab-4895-45af-88f8-fb3225a6541e",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Once students have finished brainstorming their task list, have students pair up with another pair who chose the same (or a similar) event. Direct each pair to read through the other pair’s tasks before providing feedback.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Display the peer feedback checklist and sentence starters (on the next slide) to the class while students give and read through their feedback.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Walk around and observe students as they give each other feedback. Ask guiding questions like, \"What tasks might you want to add to your own list\" and \"What tasks should be broken up into separate tasks?\""
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "acd669ab-4895-45af-88f8-fb3225a6541e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c32b75a0-affb-4678-a22e-3b53a7c1985a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3a766650-15d4-4770-b17c-67fc399c8716",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *abstraction*."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3a766650-15d4-4770-b17c-67fc399c8716",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c32b75a0-affb-4678-a22e-3b53a7c1985a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c7f93660-0f74-4c63-8fd2-2809d01170fd",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "When you look at a map, you don't see every tree, building, or streetlight – only the important features like roads, landmarks, and distances. The map removes unnecessary details while keeping the essential information needed to navigate.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c7f93660-0f74-4c63-8fd2-2809d01170fd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c32b75a0-affb-4678-a22e-3b53a7c1985a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "abc992a3-e15c-4b3b-ab4f-5c01bb3696f3",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "abc992a3-e15c-4b3b-ab4f-5c01bb3696f3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c32b75a0-affb-4678-a22e-3b53a7c1985a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4db3e6e6-5dc5-4fb4-a474-676c47f19e59",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Level 2 and Level 3. \n- **Level 2**: Students can use the AI chatbot to assist with refining their plan using abstraction.\n- **Level 3:** Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Abstraction",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Planning a School Event activity guide and the Check For Understanding question on Level 3 can be used as formative assessments of the lesson objectives."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4db3e6e6-5dc5-4fb4-a474-676c47f19e59",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c32b75a0-affb-4678-a22e-3b53a7c1985a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8de1bc9f-09d0-4c24-8214-6d18cbed1451",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8de1bc9f-09d0-4c24-8214-6d18cbed1451",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c32b75a0-affb-4678-a22e-3b53a7c1985a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f571dfe9-6bd5-4a2b-a790-d87360479f41",
      "position": 15,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How did abstraction help simplify your plan?*\n- Use Think-Pair-Share to facilitate this discussion.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should be able to articulate that abstraction helped them eliminate unnecessary details and see the big picture of what tasks they would need to complete.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How can you use the skills of decomposition and abstraction in the real world?*\n- Use the Volunteer Your Voice protocol to facilitate this discussion.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Help students make connections to ways they might already be using decomposition and abstraction in the real world. Figuring out which classes have assigned homework due the next day is an example of decomposition. Using the internet is an example of abstraction, since you don’t need to know exactly how it works in order to use it. See if students can make connections to ways engineers might use decomposition and abstraction in their jobs.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The protocol \"Volunteer Your Voice\" involves students raising their hands to volunteer information, share experiences, or answer questions based on their unique knowledge or personal experiences. This discussion technique suggests that the contributions are genuine, meaningful, and worthy of attention and respect.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f571dfe9-6bd5-4a2b-a790-d87360479f41",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c32b75a0-affb-4678-a22e-3b53a7c1985a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "325cf278-8c27-4792-b2ca-56372a3514de",
      "position": 16,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Student Survey"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "325cf278-8c27-4792-b2ca-56372a3514de",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c32b75a0-affb-4678-a22e-3b53a7c1985a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "57151b32-b07e-462b-884a-d1d07c55f63c",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the learning objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Read the Question of the Day aloud for students. Give students a moment to think about and record their answer individually in their unit guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Look for students who might be unsure of their response and provide guidance. Have them think back to the Warm Up activity and consider how decomposition and abstraction help solve a task like baking something. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The question of the day in the unit guide can be used to assess the lesson objectives."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "57151b32-b07e-462b-884a-d1d07c55f63c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "49c0d1e7-1633-49fc-9243-5171480f9c74"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "14674911-eee4-4805-9e77-f89e5408db77",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "14674911-eee4-4805-9e77-f89e5408db77",
        "lesson_activity.key": "49c0d1e7-1633-49fc-9243-5171480f9c74"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "88cef6dc-656d-45f5-a8b3-a65d828479d9",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Place students in groups of three or four.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain the Round Robin protocol. Guide students through the process of getting into small groups and designating who will share first."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "88cef6dc-656d-45f5-a8b3-a65d828479d9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "49c0d1e7-1633-49fc-9243-5171480f9c74"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bc950ef1-e913-4aa5-82ec-58e22678fa5a",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to answer the warm-up question.",
        "progression_name": "Steps to Create a Playlist"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bc950ef1-e913-4aa5-82ec-58e22678fa5a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b45c7dec-4c22-424a-8d3c-e4ab40afbcd5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ed9513c2-387f-479d-9b23-bf9c3e3ade74",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Look for students who might need help getting started. Ask: *\"What’s the first thing you’d do to if you wanted to create playlists for different events?\" or \"What categories might help organize the playlist?\"* Encourage students to think about the order of actions and any decisions they would need to make along the way.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Display students’ anonymous responses for the class. Use their answers to lead the class in a discussion about what steps were identified and what decisions were made. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students do not need to have firm ideas for how to break a problem down into these steps - that’s what they will explore today. The goal of the playlist scenario is to give students the opportunity to begin thinking about breaking down a problem into smaller steps."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ed9513c2-387f-479d-9b23-bf9c3e3ade74",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b45c7dec-4c22-424a-8d3c-e4ab40afbcd5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c4aa42f4-510f-48ce-ad3c-98a81c9ef8e2",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c4aa42f4-510f-48ce-ad3c-98a81c9ef8e2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b45c7dec-4c22-424a-8d3c-e4ab40afbcd5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "263e8dcf-1907-47d2-9e15-56bb781d4277",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Display students’ anonymous responses for the class answering the question, “What steps would you take to create a playlist?”\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** What patterns do you notice in the responses?\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Have students students practice the computational thinking skill of pattern recognition to identify similarities in their responses.\n\n\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If you feel comfortable, this is a great opportunity to model walking through the steps of students’ algorithms. Open up Spotify or another music player and have students start to give you the order of steps you need to take. Note how many steps need to be taken before you can start adding songs (login to an account, create a new playlist, create a playlist title, etc). Tell students that they will work together as a class to create a flowchart for this process."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "263e8dcf-1907-47d2-9e15-56bb781d4277",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b45c7dec-4c22-424a-8d3c-e4ab40afbcd5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "696a8ff6-97f7-4c4f-b2a9-1e5daad168bf",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Have students take out their Programming Fundamentals Unit Guide.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "696a8ff6-97f7-4c4f-b2a9-1e5daad168bf",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b45c7dec-4c22-424a-8d3c-e4ab40afbcd5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "157f0f9d-ead6-4b40-ab5e-4ef9d3c2566a",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that an algorithm is a set of step-by-step instructions to solve a problem. Algorithms often include sequencing (steps in order), selection (making decisions), and iteration (repeating steps). \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Instruct students to add the vocabulary term to their Unit Guide.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Point out the fact that in identifying some steps and decisions in creating a playlist, they dipped their toes into creating a “Playlist” algorithm. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "157f0f9d-ead6-4b40-ab5e-4ef9d3c2566a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b45c7dec-4c22-424a-8d3c-e4ab40afbcd5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9b14a1c4-f162-4a43-8a0e-f9c684de64ce",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9b14a1c4-f162-4a43-8a0e-f9c684de64ce",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b45c7dec-4c22-424a-8d3c-e4ab40afbcd5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "29e80dec-2c9f-4955-904b-07293140be7e",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the learning objectives.\n\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "29e80dec-2c9f-4955-904b-07293140be7e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b45c7dec-4c22-424a-8d3c-e4ab40afbcd5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "07dcf5f3-3fed-4f9a-afdb-a2f70121ccb6",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce this flowchart example to students. Point out that different shapes represent either taking an action or making a decision. Have students read over the chart and be prepared to share what they notice and wonder.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* What did you notice?\n* What do you wonder?\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should share what they notice and wonder about the flowchart. Encourage students to reference specific steps or decision points in their responses. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the steps (or algorithm) for designing a flowchart. Explain that we follow these steps to make the process structured and logical. \n\n\n",
        "name": "Designing an Algorithm",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "These steps are reflected in the **Understand**, **Make a plan**, and **Produce** steps of the **UMPIRE** strategy. If time permits, you can engage students with a quick recall discussion and ask the following questions:\n- How are these steps reflected in the **UMPIRE** strategy?\n- Why is it important to decompose a complex problem or break it into smaller steps?\n- How does decomposition help with creating an algorithm?\n\nReinforce that following these steps ensures clarity and helps avoid mistakes in problem-solving."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "07dcf5f3-3fed-4f9a-afdb-a2f70121ccb6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f3f34ac0-1f2d-4368-85fc-b62354f44b02"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d68c2826-cbb0-4ab8-b560-8cce900bf873",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d68c2826-cbb0-4ab8-b560-8cce900bf873",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f3f34ac0-1f2d-4368-85fc-b62354f44b02"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "23ff4c58-408c-4f9e-927c-d9605a63c36b",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Give students a few minutes to turn and talk to their elbow partner and discuss how they would go through the first three steps to decide what to wear. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "- It is okay if students don’t come up with every single step and decision point - as long as students have identified a couple steps and at least one or two decisions you can move on to start sharing\n- If students struggle to understand the point of the first step, encourage them to think about how the steps build on each other. For example, \"Understanding the problem helps you identify what decisions need to be made and how to plan the steps.\"\n- If students struggle to get started, provide a guiding question: \"What might be the first step you take before deciding what to wear?\"\n- Look for groups that identify specific decision points (e.g., \"check the weather\") and try to use those as examples in the upcoming share-out."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "23ff4c58-408c-4f9e-927c-d9605a63c36b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f3f34ac0-1f2d-4368-85fc-b62354f44b02"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fa891288-7e6d-4b28-aef7-8d813c8698e2",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Use the information on the slide to explain to students the \"Shout Out, Share Out\" protocol. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts. Have selected students who shouted out an answer record their response on a sticky note. Then use the sticky notes to build a class flowchart.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Rather than writing student responses on the board, consider having students write their response on a sticky note. Have one color represent steps (e.g. log in to my account) and another color represent decision points (e.g. decide on playlist name). This way you can build out a flowchart by rearranging decision points and steps as students provide their responses.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fa891288-7e6d-4b28-aef7-8d813c8698e2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f3f34ac0-1f2d-4368-85fc-b62354f44b02"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "339cfe78-4407-4163-8bd4-85304ce8cf27",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Go over the final step of designing an algorithm: organizing steps and decisions into a logical sequence using a flowchart. Rearrange sticky notes as needed and point out how the flowchart visually connects actions and decisions to guide the process. Explain that everyday problems, like playing music or deciding what to wear, can be broken into simple steps. Algorithms help us solve more complex problems by organizing tasks and guiding decision-making efficiently.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Highlight any sticky notes that involve doing things in a certain order (e.g. logging in to your account), decisions that need to be made (e.g. sorting songs into groups based on their energy or mood), and any steps that happened more than once (e.g. adding a song to the playlist). Connect these steps to the idea of an algorithm - a step-by-step process that often involves steps in certain order (sequencing), decision-making (selection), and repetition (iteration).\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "339cfe78-4407-4163-8bd4-85304ce8cf27",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f3f34ac0-1f2d-4368-85fc-b62354f44b02"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8f538bf4-4ab2-4592-8f79-e9ecedd47c24",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* When you hear the word ‘algorithm,’ what comes to mind?\n* How do you think Spotify chooses what to play next?\n\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Help students reflect on any biases they hold or previous experiences they have had with the word “algorithm”. Then have students think about how an AI recommendation algorithm, such as Spotify, might work. Review the flowchart you built as a class and note where the Spotify algorithm might take a different approach.\n\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students aren’t familiar with Spotify, use a different media site such as TikTok, Netflix, or YouTube to highlight the concept of an AI-powered recommendation algorithm.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8f538bf4-4ab2-4592-8f79-e9ecedd47c24",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f3f34ac0-1f2d-4368-85fc-b62354f44b02"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "dffa2adf-0eae-47bb-8d29-72e1238cc2f7",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Put students into pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair of students a handful of two different color sticky notes. Students will also need some space near their computers to arrange their sticky notes into a flowchart.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If your classroom setup doesn’t allow for students to easily work on the computer while using sticky notes to create flowcharts at their desk, consider having students use the Digital Manipulative Support resource, linked in the resources section of this lesson plan, to create their flowchart."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "dffa2adf-0eae-47bb-8d29-72e1238cc2f7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f3f34ac0-1f2d-4368-85fc-b62354f44b02"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7807355e-ab77-41ea-9e5a-b8de91e739ee",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that their task is to design an algorithm using the algorithm design steps. Let students know that they will use sticky notes for their steps and decisions points - one color for the steps or processes and one color for decision points.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Levels 2 through 6 have questions specific to the different scenarios. Have students pick **one** scenario. Then direct students to the level that matches their scenario and have them answer the questions on that level. Once they submit their answers, have them skip over the other levels and jump straight to the Check for Understanding on Level 7.\n",
        "progression_name": "Scenario Choices"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7807355e-ab77-41ea-9e5a-b8de91e739ee",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f3f34ac0-1f2d-4368-85fc-b62354f44b02"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b7f96039-4268-492f-987c-7deb5b7a3f80",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Make sure that students are only answering questions for one scenario. Check that students are clearly identifying steps and decision points in their algorithms. Ask questions like: \"What is the goal of your algorithm?\" or \"Does your flowchart account for all possible outcomes?\"",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "- Ensure students are using sticky notes for steps (processes) and decision points in order to make rearranging steps easier.\n- Encourage students to start simple and add details later if they feel stuck. For example, “Start with the first major step. What needs to happen first? What’s the next logical step?”\n- If students struggle with decision points, guide them by asking: “What question would your algorithm need to answer to move forward?”"
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The responses in Levels 2 through 6 can be used to formatively assess the lesson objectives. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b7f96039-4268-492f-987c-7deb5b7a3f80",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f3f34ac0-1f2d-4368-85fc-b62354f44b02"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1ed541af-36d6-4f5a-811e-e0f2279fee02",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1ed541af-36d6-4f5a-811e-e0f2279fee02",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f3f34ac0-1f2d-4368-85fc-b62354f44b02"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a3d9ecde-432d-4c0a-a30b-bc703d966980",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Instruct students to pair up with another group to share their flowcharts, use the questions on the slide to provide constructive feedback, and then revise their flowcharts based on that feedback. Emphasize that the goal is to make their algorithms clearer and more complete.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Check that students are giving meaningful feedback and incorporating it into their revisions. Ask questions like: *\"What feedback are you using to improve your flowchart?\"* or *\"How does your revision address missing steps or outcomes?\"",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If you wish to collect students’ algorithm flowcharts, you can have students attach their finished flowchart sticky notes to a poster and display everyone’s flowcharts. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a3d9ecde-432d-4c0a-a30b-bc703d966980",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f3f34ac0-1f2d-4368-85fc-b62354f44b02"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5e791e23-a427-42e7-a572-00f996a64471",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5e791e23-a427-42e7-a572-00f996a64471",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f3f34ac0-1f2d-4368-85fc-b62354f44b02"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "08cd6fbf-d36a-4c8e-af6d-61c1c4765144",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Level 7 on Code Studio to answer the Check for Understanding questions.",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The responses in Level 7 can be used to formatively assess the lesson objectives. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "08cd6fbf-d36a-4c8e-af6d-61c1c4765144",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f3f34ac0-1f2d-4368-85fc-b62354f44b02"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "29d7c2cb-49ce-4d97-8fc0-90499f87a9b0",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "29d7c2cb-49ce-4d97-8fc0-90499f87a9b0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f3f34ac0-1f2d-4368-85fc-b62354f44b02"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "20e47a8d-2178-4394-9fbb-7dd8185425b3",
      "position": 15,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *What challenges did you face when deciding what to keep, delete, or highlight?*\n- *How might AI handle similar challenges?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Help students reflect on the challenges they faced when designing their algorithms, such as balancing fairness or handling multiple outcomes. Encourage them to connect these challenges to how AI might tackle similar problems, highlighting both its strengths (e.g., efficiency) and limitations (e.g., bias or lack of context). The goal is for students to recognize the importance of thoughtful algorithm design in addressing complex, real-world issues.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "This is a deep topic and could spark a lot of discussion. Unless you have the additional time to devote to this discussion, try to keep discussion concise to stay with a 5 minute timeframe. Ensure students that the topics of societal impact and using AI ethically will be revisited. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "20e47a8d-2178-4394-9fbb-7dd8185425b3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f3f34ac0-1f2d-4368-85fc-b62354f44b02"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5805f6e9-f412-4a5b-afbd-7c8595e1482b",
      "position": 16,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Student Survey"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5805f6e9-f412-4a5b-afbd-7c8595e1482b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f3f34ac0-1f2d-4368-85fc-b62354f44b02"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c6960a8f-1133-48d9-8276-0f4a7850375a",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Instruct students to write their responses in their Unit Guide. After two or three minutes, facilitate a quick sharing activity (e.g., Whip Around or Popcorn Share), calling on a few students to share their ideas.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The question of the day in the Unit Guide can be used to assess the lesson objectives."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c6960a8f-1133-48d9-8276-0f4a7850375a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "dc416934-a45b-4896-83b2-2da6999a9734"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6fa481a2-cfdd-44ad-929d-b9c2f946876d",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the key vocabulary\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6fa481a2-cfdd-44ad-929d-b9c2f946876d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "dc416934-a45b-4896-83b2-2da6999a9734"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9aad5ef3-0c75-4d0f-8ebf-10ecd2b163c4",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair of students several sticky notes.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students work with their partner to brainstorm different types of information.",
        "name": "What's in a Variable?",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students are struggling to get started, prompt them with categories or examples based on apps they know and use – like Spotify (music preferences) or TikTok (like videos, username). Encourage students to think broadly – personal data, progress tracking, or anything an app might need to \"remember\" to work well."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9aad5ef3-0c75-4d0f-8ebf-10ecd2b163c4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5f31b026-872f-4252-bc73-7e50bbf98079"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6fc664b8-dd14-475a-8b67-86a51545431f",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6fc664b8-dd14-475a-8b67-86a51545431f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5f31b026-872f-4252-bc73-7e50bbf98079"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "92672583-9ea1-4a8b-9c3c-449e0e8c3634",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Have students look at their sticky notes and group them by type of information. Prompt them to sort by categories like:\n- Numbers (e.g., scores, steps)\n- Text (e.g., names, favorite artists)\n- True/False (e.g., is premium user?)\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As students sort and discuss, listen for sticky notes that don't easily fit in a category and misconceptions (e.g., thinking a number stored as a string is a number).",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students are unsure how to group their notes, suggest they focus on how the app would use that information – does it calculate with it? display it as text? check if something is true? This gets them thinking in terms of data types without needing formal vocabulary yet."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "92672583-9ea1-4a8b-9c3c-449e0e8c3634",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5f31b026-872f-4252-bc73-7e50bbf98079"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cbb87a5d-fbdf-48fa-a9da-2f7355d43336",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cbb87a5d-fbdf-48fa-a9da-2f7355d43336",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5f31b026-872f-4252-bc73-7e50bbf98079"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "950c53e0-6df6-44c8-b6b3-9869e452db9e",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "950c53e0-6df6-44c8-b6b3-9869e452db9e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5f31b026-872f-4252-bc73-7e50bbf98079"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "54e81641-8e9f-4026-b7e7-9e1c70e947ff",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Have students take out their Programming Fundamentals Unit Guide.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Introduction to Python"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "54e81641-8e9f-4026-b7e7-9e1c70e947ff",
        "lesson_activity.key": "629560fd-3648-4185-ab22-93d6c44ddccf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d2877af5-7958-4ced-8b74-a90ae0455c1f",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Python is one of the most popular programming languages in the world — it's used by app creators, game developers, AI engineers, and even students like you!",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d2877af5-7958-4ced-8b74-a90ae0455c1f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "629560fd-3648-4185-ab22-93d6c44ddccf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f7bc315b-d1c6-491f-bd78-013cff837816",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that students will be learning Python programming in this unit. Make it real and relatable by highlighting examples like how Python is used to build games (like Minecraft mods), power recommendation systems (like Netflix and Spotify), and is even used in AI tools like ChatGPT."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f7bc315b-d1c6-491f-bd78-013cff837816",
        "lesson_activity.key": "629560fd-3648-4185-ab22-93d6c44ddccf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8476b4ac-8144-4c17-a1ef-aa1f5f223bfd",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Today, you'll write programs that store and update this kind of data using variables.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8476b4ac-8144-4c17-a1ef-aa1f5f223bfd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "629560fd-3648-4185-ab22-93d6c44ddccf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0865eebf-0540-47e3-953a-709c59221d3c",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *variable*. Use a few of the sticky notes from the warm up as examples, asking students what they might name each of piece of information. Emphasize that the name of the variable should describe what it is storing so it makes sense to them and anyone else reading their code.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *data type*.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Refer back to the sticky note examples from the warm up. For example:\n- If my app is tracking steps, what kind of data is that? (number)\n- If it's storing your username? (text)\n- If it's checking if a user is logged in? (True/False)\n\nReinforce that this is a thinking move they're already doing – they already sorted this information in their brainstorm. Now we're giving it the programming name: data type."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0865eebf-0540-47e3-953a-709c59221d3c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "629560fd-3648-4185-ab22-93d6c44ddccf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ead4c788-c33a-45a1-9eb5-7761f5d5d3b7",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ead4c788-c33a-45a1-9eb5-7761f5d5d3b7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "629560fd-3648-4185-ab22-93d6c44ddccf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8aad7421-8b8d-40bc-b167-fd6c9c7a67cd",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What do you think will be printed when this code runs?*\n- Have students turn and talk with a partner or jot their predictions on paper.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize that the program defines two variables: `username` and `level`. They should also realize that `print()` outputs the label followed by the value."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8aad7421-8b8d-40bc-b167-fd6c9c7a67cd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "629560fd-3648-4185-ab22-93d6c44ddccf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ca83e76c-1779-43f2-8bbf-382d081d1f66",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "This is our first look at real Python code! The computer reads this line by line – first it saves the value `\"Kai\"` in the variable `username`, and the number `4` in `level`. Then it prints both using the `print()` function.",
        "remarks": true,
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students often confuse the `=` sign in programming with the equals sign in math. When reading the code, be sure to read the `=` operator as \"gets\" instead of \"equals\" to emphasize putting something into a box rather than checking if two things are equal."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ca83e76c-1779-43f2-8bbf-382d081d1f66",
        "lesson_activity.key": "629560fd-3648-4185-ab22-93d6c44ddccf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "676f3c64-927c-4e74-9fbd-673dfee4218c",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "676f3c64-927c-4e74-9fbd-673dfee4218c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "629560fd-3648-4185-ab22-93d6c44ddccf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ace57a77-2f25-4871-9651-f6d71b437f6a",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *snake_case*. Click through the animated slide to show examples of variable names, emphasizing how the first one follows naming conventions while the second will cause an error because of the space between `user` and `name`.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Emphasize to students that, while Python won't stop you from using names like `x1` or `a`, we want to get into the habit of naming variables in a way that's clear and meaningful.\n\nIf students are familiar with camelCase from another language or tool, you can point out that this is Python's version of a readable naming convention."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ace57a77-2f25-4871-9651-f6d71b437f6a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "629560fd-3648-4185-ab22-93d6c44ddccf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "614c9712-5fe4-4e1b-8c42-454f93b91413",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "614c9712-5fe4-4e1b-8c42-454f93b91413",
        "lesson_activity.key": "629560fd-3648-4185-ab22-93d6c44ddccf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6490bd27-44e2-4f1a-80d8-55a06e35b255",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Use the chart to briefly walk through each row, reading the type, what it stores, and the example.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "You don't need to go deep into each one yet – just give students a first look at the terms and connect them to earlier examples from the warm up brainstorm."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6490bd27-44e2-4f1a-80d8-55a06e35b255",
        "lesson_activity.key": "629560fd-3648-4185-ab22-93d6c44ddccf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2b61d9ae-c2a3-4fe9-a5a0-8efd0da2e5ae",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2b61d9ae-c2a3-4fe9-a5a0-8efd0da2e5ae",
        "lesson_activity.key": "629560fd-3648-4185-ab22-93d6c44ddccf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "89006754-9115-4cc0-b764-b8ef1d782028",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Here's a piece of Python code that creates a variable called `name` and stores the value `'Manda'` – but when we run it, we get a message saying it failed. Let's look at the feedback from the system. This message is trying to help us figure out what's going wrong.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "89006754-9115-4cc0-b764-b8ef1d782028",
        "lesson_activity.key": "629560fd-3648-4185-ab22-93d6c44ddccf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "51a43b0f-91ab-4aaa-8336-beebc6634d0d",
      "position": 15,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What is the validation telling you?*\n- Ask students to rephrase the error message in their own words.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should begin seeing error messages as useful clues and note that a `print()` statement is needed.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Reinforce that errors are part of the process. Every programmer – even pros – sees these kinds of messages all the time. The goal isn't go avoid errors, but to learn how to read them and respond."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "51a43b0f-91ab-4aaa-8336-beebc6634d0d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "629560fd-3648-4185-ab22-93d6c44ddccf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "dcf51f18-10b6-45cd-840a-f82ee13592c0",
      "position": 16,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "dcf51f18-10b6-45cd-840a-f82ee13592c0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "629560fd-3648-4185-ab22-93d6c44ddccf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f9e96760-2b3a-46d0-b48a-9d3ba406b566",
      "position": 17,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *debug*."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f9e96760-2b3a-46d0-b48a-9d3ba406b566",
        "lesson_activity.key": "629560fd-3648-4185-ab22-93d6c44ddccf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "29036d5e-2354-480e-aa27-22c71f7b4793",
      "position": 18,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Every programmer – beginner to expert – spends time debugging. It's how we learn!",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "29036d5e-2354-480e-aa27-22c71f7b4793",
        "lesson_activity.key": "629560fd-3648-4185-ab22-93d6c44ddccf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "376a96d0-60f9-45c9-81a6-2d39b55e7b64",
      "position": 19,
      "properties": {
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Share that debugging is not failure – it's a key step in the problem-solving process, and often the most valuable."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "376a96d0-60f9-45c9-81a6-2d39b55e7b64",
        "lesson_activity.key": "629560fd-3648-4185-ab22-93d6c44ddccf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bcc8c27a-a204-4b86-a6ed-8ef9ba8ceea9",
      "position": 20,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 4, Level 1 to complete Levels 1 through 10.\n- **Level #1:** In Python Lab, students run a program that prints a message.\n- **Level #2:** Students add a comment at the top of the file describing what the program does.\n- **Level #3:** Students complete a choice level where they add a variable and assign it a value, then print it.\n- **Level #4:** Students complete a choice level where they change the value of an existing variable and print the new result.\n- **Level #5:** Students complete a choice level where they are given two `int` variables and write code that adds, subtracts, multiplies, and divides them.\n- **Level #6:** Students complete a choice level where they are given a mix of variables (`int`, `str`, `bool`) and have to predict or write code for which types work with which operations (e.g., `+` works for numbers but not for `bool`).\n- **Level #7:** Students complete a choice level where they are given a buggy program that includes a missing quote in a string and a misspelled variable name. They must fix both issues to get the code to run.\n- **Level #8:** Students complete a vocabulary Check Your Understanding question.\n- **Level #9:** Students complete a Check Your Understanding question.\n- **Level #10:** Students choose a topic (e.g., music, soccer, fashion, games), and create three variables (one for each data type). They use at least one operation, then write a few print statements to show that the program outputs.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Exploring Variables",
        "progression_name": "Exploring Variables"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bcc8c27a-a204-4b86-a6ed-8ef9ba8ceea9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "629560fd-3648-4185-ab22-93d6c44ddccf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5f5ab43b-5dff-40db-8a11-dc050b390958",
      "position": 21,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Check Your Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5f5ab43b-5dff-40db-8a11-dc050b390958",
        "lesson_activity.key": "629560fd-3648-4185-ab22-93d6c44ddccf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "afeeef49-fe19-446b-819f-71be547afb1a",
      "position": 22,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "My Life, My Variables"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "afeeef49-fe19-446b-819f-71be547afb1a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "629560fd-3648-4185-ab22-93d6c44ddccf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b4ded1e4-a85a-4be7-bcda-9842b2cc4e43",
      "position": 23,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As students work through the levels, move around the room and observe how they are approaching the coding tasks. If students encounter a bug, encourage them to read the error message and make a thoughtful change. Ask students:\n- What is your variable storing?\n- How do you know that part of your code is working?\n- What did you change when you got an error?\n\nReinforce that making mistakes and debugging are expected parts of the programming process. Celebrate perseverance and curiosity as students explore how their code works.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Levels 3 through 7 are choice levels. Encourage students to try at least one and challenge themselves."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b4ded1e4-a85a-4be7-bcda-9842b2cc4e43",
        "lesson_activity.key": "629560fd-3648-4185-ab22-93d6c44ddccf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "51d0ea45-54bd-4525-9136-3260b2caeae7",
      "position": 24,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "51d0ea45-54bd-4525-9136-3260b2caeae7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "629560fd-3648-4185-ab22-93d6c44ddccf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4c9550c5-2fad-442c-9a04-1887894811da",
      "position": 25,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *With your partner, share one variable you created and how it works. What did you do to fix an error in your program? How did you improve your code today?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:**  Students should reflect on what they practiced – identifying variables they created (name, type, purpose), recognizing moments when they encountered and fixed bugs, and thinking about how they made their code clearer or more effective.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Listen for students using terminology like variable names, data types, or print statements, examples of debugging (e.g., \"I forgot the quotes\" or \"I misspelled the variable name\"), and students encouraging each other or asking thoughtful questions.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use this discussion as a chance to surface a few \"glows and grows\" with the class afterward. Call on one or two students to share an error they overcame."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4c9550c5-2fad-442c-9a04-1887894811da",
        "lesson_activity.key": "629560fd-3648-4185-ab22-93d6c44ddccf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5ec58af4-aa7a-4a1e-9130-462332c8e3f9",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students respond to the Question of the Day in their unit guides.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Key Vocabulary.",
        "name": "Question of the Day Reflection"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5ec58af4-aa7a-4a1e-9130-462332c8e3f9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7c149ce9-7f1a-4aeb-bdc8-c031405bb9da"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1ac576af-f680-4f19-adf9-8f61382cf2cf",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Read the list of instructions aloud or have a student read them. Ask students to predict what the delivery drone will do by sketching its path or discussing with a partner. Prompt students to consider:\n- What direction the drone is facing when it starts\n- What path it will follow on the grid\n- What colors it will paint along the way\n- Where it will end up if it starts facing up\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Walk through each instruction to demonstrate the solution. Ask students to check their predictions:\n- *Did your drawing or mental map match the solution?*\n- *Did anyone have a different answer? Let's talk about why.*",
        "name": "Following Instructions",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students made mistakes, celebrate productive struggle! Highlight how each instruction affects the drone's position and state, building intuition for sequencing commands – a key part of today's lesson."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1ac576af-f680-4f19-adf9-8f61382cf2cf",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b1d1e1b6-b94a-4d7c-a165-dfd994c688b8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f1c8468a-0003-4661-857d-9ab6ada64dec",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f1c8468a-0003-4661-857d-9ab6ada64dec",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b1d1e1b6-b94a-4d7c-a165-dfd994c688b8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "479b3292-1ec6-4933-b511-282a341e4269",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "479b3292-1ec6-4933-b511-282a341e4269",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b1d1e1b6-b94a-4d7c-a165-dfd994c688b8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ebc2d506-655f-46cd-a3bf-d1709f6d2e11",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Have students take out their Programming Fundamentals Unit Guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce students to The Neighborhood. Point out that the grid is 8 spaces wide and 8 spaces tall, with coordinates starting at (0, 0) in the top-left.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Meet the Painter",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Reinforce the idea that this is a 2D coordinate system, which they'll use to understand the Painter's movements."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ebc2d506-655f-46cd-a3bf-d1709f6d2e11",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e219d7cf-34d0-4406-94e2-8a5ff875e6e1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b31f3851-c6a0-4446-9276-a6357d995d75",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b31f3851-c6a0-4446-9276-a6357d995d75",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e219d7cf-34d0-4406-94e2-8a5ff875e6e1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "78837b73-a17b-4745-9f2a-02470b97715d",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Point out obstacles like the traffic cone, wall, and sidewalk. Explain that the `Painter` can't move on or through these obstacles.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the `Painter` as the object students will be controlling in their code. Emphasize that the `Painter` already has built-in abilities – move, turn, and paint. Students won't define how these actions work; instead, they'll learn how to tell the `Painter` what to do and when.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students ask how the `Painter` knows how to do these things, let them know it's because it was created from a class – they'll learn more about that shortly.\n\nRefer back to the warm up if needed: \"Just like we gave the drone a sequence of instructions, we'll give the `Painter` a sequence of commands.\""
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "78837b73-a17b-4745-9f2a-02470b97715d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e219d7cf-34d0-4406-94e2-8a5ff875e6e1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e40ec127-174f-476d-b6c8-6b30aa25a4e2",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e40ec127-174f-476d-b6c8-6b30aa25a4e2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e219d7cf-34d0-4406-94e2-8a5ff875e6e1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8b49e9cf-39a2-4700-a2b3-f08afad03b28",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain the default conditions for every new `Painter` object – at the top-left corner of the grid (0, 0), facing East, with 0 units of paint.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Clarify that \"faces East\" means moving right on the grid – this is often the first directional detail students mix up."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8b49e9cf-39a2-4700-a2b3-f08afad03b28",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e219d7cf-34d0-4406-94e2-8a5ff875e6e1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e8a20912-3a41-4694-b908-88100266bf67",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e8a20912-3a41-4694-b908-88100266bf67",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e219d7cf-34d0-4406-94e2-8a5ff875e6e1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a243e63c-8ec1-4503-ba0f-e325e18d05ed",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 5, Level 1 to complete Levels 1 through 6.\n- **Level #1:** In Python Lab, students are given a few lines of code and asked to predict what the `Painter` will do. Then they run the program to compare the result to their prediction.\n- **Level #2:** Students write code to create a new `Painter` object and call one method to move it forward.\n- **Level #3:** Students complete a choice level where they are given a partially complete program and asked to add code so the `Painter` reaches the intended location.\n- **Level #4:** Students complete a choice level where they modify a program so that the `Painter` ends in a different position or faces a different direction.\n- **Level #5:** Students complete a choice level where they create two `Painter` objects.\n- **Level #6:** Students complete a Check Your Understanding.",
        "progression_name": "Meet the Painter"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a243e63c-8ec1-4503-ba0f-e325e18d05ed",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e219d7cf-34d0-4406-94e2-8a5ff875e6e1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "87e8bd80-4b50-4c3a-94fc-4ec01d281735",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Check Your Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "87e8bd80-4b50-4c3a-94fc-4ec01d281735",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e219d7cf-34d0-4406-94e2-8a5ff875e6e1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "39e6ccda-c2a5-4c88-8159-fda5483f9823",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Watch for students confusing the `Painter`'s starting direction or misplacing method calls. Prompt them to read each line carefully and visualize the `Painter`'s actions.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Levels 3 through 5 are choice levels. Encourage students to try at least one and challenge themselves."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "39e6ccda-c2a5-4c88-8159-fda5483f9823",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e219d7cf-34d0-4406-94e2-8a5ff875e6e1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a2c2dadc-3900-4a67-9812-fc89b655af90",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a2c2dadc-3900-4a67-9812-fc89b655af90",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e219d7cf-34d0-4406-94e2-8a5ff875e6e1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "333a492f-5c8a-44bf-8365-f787f2ec48ea",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain the import line. Emphasize that Python doesn't know what a `Painter` is unless you import it first.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain that when students write `alice = Painter()`, they are creating a new `Painter` object and giving it a name (`alice`) so they can control it.\n- `Painter()` tells Python to create a new object using the `Painter` blueprint (they'll learn more about blueprints/classes soon).\n- `alice =` gives that new object a name so we can refer to it in our code.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Moving and Turning",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students ask why they need to name the `Painter`, reinforce that it's just like saving a file or naming a variable – it lets us refer to and control that specific object."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "333a492f-5c8a-44bf-8365-f787f2ec48ea",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e219d7cf-34d0-4406-94e2-8a5ff875e6e1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8768800e-9e6d-470e-8bee-a3cf8ad2f646",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8768800e-9e6d-470e-8bee-a3cf8ad2f646",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e219d7cf-34d0-4406-94e2-8a5ff875e6e1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "90e808b2-6cee-4d38-913a-9005c340ea6d",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "A class is like a set of instructions or a blueprint. It doesn't *do* anything on its own, but it tells Python how to create something – like a `Painter` – that can do specific tasks.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "90e808b2-6cee-4d38-913a-9005c340ea6d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e219d7cf-34d0-4406-94e2-8a5ff875e6e1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0f1c1686-aca9-4be4-a0c8-32849f7ecf9a",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0f1c1686-aca9-4be4-a0c8-32849f7ecf9a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e219d7cf-34d0-4406-94e2-8a5ff875e6e1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "73836f21-e0ba-4ccd-8a84-01a15f1f003b",
      "position": 15,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to introduce the concept of a *class*as the foundation for creating objects in code.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students are not defining their own classes in this unit. They just need to understand that objects come from classes, and they're using a pre-built one."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "73836f21-e0ba-4ccd-8a84-01a15f1f003b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e219d7cf-34d0-4406-94e2-8a5ff875e6e1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6d67aa0d-4aaf-4b00-ad16-6ac1c44c168f",
      "position": 16,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6d67aa0d-4aaf-4b00-ad16-6ac1c44c168f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e219d7cf-34d0-4406-94e2-8a5ff875e6e1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ca5620ee-1cfd-4559-9348-ee35c40d1a43",
      "position": 17,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Once you've created a `Painter`, it becomes an object. That object has things it knows – like where it is – and things it can do – like move or paint.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ca5620ee-1cfd-4559-9348-ee35c40d1a43",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e219d7cf-34d0-4406-94e2-8a5ff875e6e1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ae27c96b-e63c-411b-9a3d-679792a589cb",
      "position": 18,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to define *object*.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Help students distinguish between attributes (stored information) and methods (actions). You can prompt them to name examples of both for familiar things (e.g., a phone, a car, a video game character)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ae27c96b-e63c-411b-9a3d-679792a589cb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e219d7cf-34d0-4406-94e2-8a5ff875e6e1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d27dacd3-ef30-47e5-b86c-18833f344548",
      "position": 19,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d27dacd3-ef30-47e5-b86c-18833f344548",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e219d7cf-34d0-4406-94e2-8a5ff875e6e1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f7a0ff17-0196-40b0-9d2e-f460384be5c7",
      "position": 20,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Can you think of something from your life – like a person, pet, or app – that could be described as an object in code? What would its attributes and methods be?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students might say: \"My phone is an object — it knows its battery level (attribute) and can take a photo (method).\" The goal is to give them a solid, memorable mental model.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain that they can create multiple `Painter` objects. They both come from the same class (blueprint), but they are completely independent from one another. Be sure to clarify that `alice` and `bob` each have their own position, direction, and paint amount. We can give them different instructions, and they won't affect each other.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students may assume that calling `Painter()` twice creates the same object reused. Reinforce that each call to `Painter()` creates a new object with its own state."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f7a0ff17-0196-40b0-9d2e-f460384be5c7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e219d7cf-34d0-4406-94e2-8a5ff875e6e1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "81b03eb4-1b85-4a40-8b16-62106c1a861e",
      "position": 21,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "81b03eb4-1b85-4a40-8b16-62106c1a861e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e219d7cf-34d0-4406-94e2-8a5ff875e6e1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8026bb26-b024-44d7-8f24-f669007c184a",
      "position": 22,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *method*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain how to use dot notation to call a method on an object."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8026bb26-b024-44d7-8f24-f669007c184a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e219d7cf-34d0-4406-94e2-8a5ff875e6e1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5fd58e5d-4e33-4c60-9311-05dcb862bda9",
      "position": 23,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *If the `Painter` can only turn left, how could we make it turn right?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should realize that turning left three times has the same effect as turning right once. This encourages creative problem-solving using the tools available – a core idea in programming.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Solving Problems in The Neighborhood",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "This is a great opportunity to highlight how constraints in programming can lead to clever workarounds — a common experience even for professional coders."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5fd58e5d-4e33-4c60-9311-05dcb862bda9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e219d7cf-34d0-4406-94e2-8a5ff875e6e1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "feb4e3b1-ebb0-4523-862e-631a90717f30",
      "position": 24,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "feb4e3b1-ebb0-4523-862e-631a90717f30",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e219d7cf-34d0-4406-94e2-8a5ff875e6e1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6b4aec7f-577c-40a2-b378-ab7638dd4c64",
      "position": 25,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Before you jump into writing real code, it helps to map out your steps in everyday language. That's what pseudocode is for – it helps you plan.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6b4aec7f-577c-40a2-b378-ab7638dd4c64",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e219d7cf-34d0-4406-94e2-8a5ff875e6e1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "19b1bf5e-276c-46b0-8355-311c203a3a30",
      "position": 26,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *pseudocode*.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to write pseudocode when they're stuck or unsure how to start. It's a great way to clarify their thinking and reduce trial-and-error coding."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "19b1bf5e-276c-46b0-8355-311c203a3a30",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e219d7cf-34d0-4406-94e2-8a5ff875e6e1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4210d125-6942-40b7-8d36-5a23d4eee09e",
      "position": 27,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Remember that our UMPIRE strategy is like your game plan when you're solving a problem in code. If you're stuck, go back to the top of the list and walk through it step by step.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4210d125-6942-40b7-8d36-5a23d4eee09e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e219d7cf-34d0-4406-94e2-8a5ff875e6e1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b4ad4684-7880-4ab7-8dbc-33dc6de1844a",
      "position": 28,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Reintroduce students to the UMPIRE strategy, which helps organize their thinking while solving coding problems.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to refer back to **UMPIRE** as they work through the upcoming challenges. This strategy is especially helpful when debugging or planning more complex programs later in the unit. There is an optional activity guide available in the resource section for students to document their **UMPIRE** process.\n\nShare the following strategy steps with your students if they need a reminder for how to implement them with a programming task:\n- **Understand:** Define or restate the problem\n- **Make a Plan:** Ideas for solving the problem - could involve writing pseudocode\n- **Produce:** Write your code!\n- **Inspect:** Trace and test your code as you develop it. Ask for feedback, as necessary\n- **Refine:** Iterate your design until it meets your criteria\n- **Explain:** Talk though your code, your choices, or your process with a peer\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b4ad4684-7880-4ab7-8dbc-33dc6de1844a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e219d7cf-34d0-4406-94e2-8a5ff875e6e1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4c4f0ae0-6aa0-4062-8191-39e0d5151ed0",
      "position": 29,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4c4f0ae0-6aa0-4062-8191-39e0d5151ed0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e219d7cf-34d0-4406-94e2-8a5ff875e6e1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "06aa0f2f-808e-4c16-a3e8-777512767ab7",
      "position": 30,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 5, Level 7 to complete Levels 7 through 11.\n- **Level #7:** Students debug code with an error.\n- **Level #8:** Students are given code where the `Painter`'s `turn_left()` and `move()` methods are out of order and result in an incorrect outcome.\n- **Level #9:** Students complete a choice level where they have the Painter move and turn.\n- **Level #10:** Students complete a vocabulary Check Your Understanding.\n- **Level #11:** Students complete a Check Your Understanding.",
        "progression_name": "Moving and Turning"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "06aa0f2f-808e-4c16-a3e8-777512767ab7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e219d7cf-34d0-4406-94e2-8a5ff875e6e1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f317e5d5-6c61-4874-9700-3b9ff526742f",
      "position": 31,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Check Your Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f317e5d5-6c61-4874-9700-3b9ff526742f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e219d7cf-34d0-4406-94e2-8a5ff875e6e1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cba039be-cc8c-4c4e-9a84-16d156495857",
      "position": 32,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Check that students are using parentheses when calling methods, giving method calls in a logical order (e.g., move before paint), and can explain what their code is doing and why. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Level 9 is a choice level. Encourage students to try at least one and challenge themselves."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cba039be-cc8c-4c4e-9a84-16d156495857",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e219d7cf-34d0-4406-94e2-8a5ff875e6e1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e6cc8b7d-9d57-46c6-b9db-c90580efae84",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students respond to the Question of the Day in their unit guides.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Key Vocabulary.",
        "name": "Question of the Day Reflection"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e6cc8b7d-9d57-46c6-b9db-c90580efae84",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3b86095e-2c64-4946-84c0-63d0f3cb2f03"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8f3ba86a-8341-4ed2-b901-92440228bcfc",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What's something you always do in the same order? Think about a morning routine, a sports move, or something in a game you play. What are the steps? Why is the order important?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students recognize that many everyday actions follow a specific sequence. The goal is to connect this idea to the importance of writing code in a logical order, just like a set of steps.",
        "name": "Life Functions",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Guide students to consider examples that are clear sequences (e.g., brushing teeth, cooking eggs, shooting a free throw). Choose a few to highlight that map easily to a \"function\" idea later."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8f3ba86a-8341-4ed2-b901-92440228bcfc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4caded04-ab9c-4308-a562-19ecf308c9f4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "dedfa9f9-5467-4d16-81db-180a43219650",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "dedfa9f9-5467-4d16-81db-180a43219650",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4caded04-ab9c-4308-a562-19ecf308c9f4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3ae25641-091a-4eb3-aa75-73a130ec28c5",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3ae25641-091a-4eb3-aa75-73a130ec28c5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4caded04-ab9c-4308-a562-19ecf308c9f4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4a783761-32ea-4dfc-85e5-955e9d76a9a3",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Have students take out their Programming Fundamentals Unit Guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *function*.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4a783761-32ea-4dfc-85e5-955e9d76a9a3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "87e468a2-14c1-4615-9956-6e79c0fc780f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2332c266-0059-47fb-95de-3635056dde50",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "A function is like a named recipe or a mini program inside your program. You give it a name – like \"make pancakes\" – and then define the steps it should follow. This way, whenever you want to make pancakes, you just call the function instead of writing out the steps every time.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2332c266-0059-47fb-95de-3635056dde50",
        "lesson_activity.key": "87e468a2-14c1-4615-9956-6e79c0fc780f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "204e75a8-5d7e-4eef-a99c-7d4299b1ad30",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Place students in groups of three or four.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Provide each group with a deck of Instruction Cards and a Function Template sheet.\n\n",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "You're the Function!"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "204e75a8-5d7e-4eef-a99c-7d4299b1ad30",
        "lesson_activity.key": "87e468a2-14c1-4615-9956-6e79c0fc780f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "25c83574-e25c-4333-a0b9-4fb924164bbe",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Direct students to choose three to five instruction cards with their group. Groups should work together to organize these into a meaningful sequence, then give the sequence a name (e.g., \"make silly move\" or \"dance\"). Students act out their function or simulate it on paper.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Watch for groups choosing clear, logical sequences and naming their functions descriptively. Support students that are stuck on sequencing or naming. Listen for opportunities to highlight creative or well-named functions later.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "You could choose to have groups trade their function with another group. Ask them to act out or simulate the new function and \"debug\" it – look for steps that are missing, unclear, or out of order. This can give students a chance to practice interpreting other people's instructions and thinking critically about how well a function communicates its purpose."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "25c83574-e25c-4333-a0b9-4fb924164bbe",
        "lesson_activity.key": "87e468a2-14c1-4615-9956-6e79c0fc780f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "20934670-cf99-47a0-a105-8608fcd5214d",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "20934670-cf99-47a0-a105-8608fcd5214d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "87e468a2-14c1-4615-9956-6e79c0fc780f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a071346d-bb95-4d2b-bc71-4bb3a561fafb",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Why was it helpful to name your sequence of steps?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:**  Students should recognize that naming the sequence makes it easier to describe and reuse, helps others understand what the function does, and saves time by avoiding repetition."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a071346d-bb95-4d2b-bc71-4bb3a561fafb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "87e468a2-14c1-4615-9956-6e79c0fc780f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ac2739f4-54c7-4d22-81f4-70c84f204e10",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "When we notice patterns in code, we can group them together and give them a name. In computer science, this is called abstraction – and we use functions to do it!",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ac2739f4-54c7-4d22-81f4-70c84f204e10",
        "lesson_activity.key": "87e468a2-14c1-4615-9956-6e79c0fc780f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8ca0d3d7-f129-4e93-a1e0-b3d0c5e7c5dc",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How would someone else know what your function does?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize that a clear and descriptive function name helps others understand what the function does. They should understand that good naming makes it easier to read code without having to look at every individual step inside the function. When function names describe actions, they make the code more readable and easier to maintain over time.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What would happen if one of the steps in your function were missing?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:**  Students should understand that each step in a function matters, and missing a step can break the function or cause it to behave incorrectly. This sets up the importance of precision and debugging in programming."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8ca0d3d7-f129-4e93-a1e0-b3d0c5e7c5dc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "87e468a2-14c1-4615-9956-6e79c0fc780f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "87ffc087-16ef-4641-8b22-f870a87e11d9",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "This is just like in real code – if even one line is missing, a function might not work the way we expect. That's why we need to test and debug our code carefully.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "87ffc087-16ef-4641-8b22-f870a87e11d9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "87e468a2-14c1-4615-9956-6e79c0fc780f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a22c2487-d84b-4cc7-86e4-b03e033375d1",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that whenever they are learning about a new coding concept, they will annotate a block of code in our Unit Guide. This means that they will either fill in the blanks by writing pieces of code or add descriptions to the pieces of code. Walk students through this first example of annotating code to ensure they understand.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that we define a function with the word **def**, which tells Python we're *defining* a function. Have students fill in the blank on their Unit Guide by adding the word def.\n\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that we then give the function a name. This should describe what the function does. Have students fill in the blank in their Unit Guide by adding the description “Function name” above the name of the function.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that after the name, we add parentheses and a colon. Have students finish the first line of the function definition in their Unit Guide by adding the parentheses and colon.\n\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that the steps that the function performs go *underneath*, and they must be indented. Python uses indentation to know what's inside the function. Tell students to use the Tab key to indent their code.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that once you've defined the function, you can call it by using its name with parentheses. Have students fill in the blank in their Unit Guide code to match what’s on the slide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 6, Level 1 to complete Levels 1 through 8.\n- **Level #1:** In Python Lab, students complete a function that prints something and then call it.\n- **Level #2:** Students are given a defined function but the call is missing parentheses.\n- **Level #3:** Students are given a working function and must add code to call it three times in a row.\n- **Level #4:** Students debug a broken function definition with missing or incorrect syntax.\n- **Level #5:** Students complete a choice level where they are given a function and add a line of code to it.\n- **Level #6:** Students complete a choice level where they are given two small functions that are already defined and must write a new function that calls both in order.\n- **Level #7:** Students complete a vocabulary Check Your Understanding.\n- **Level #8:** Students complete a Check Your Understanding.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Exploring Functions",
        "progression_name": "Exploring Functions"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a22c2487-d84b-4cc7-86e4-b03e033375d1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "87e468a2-14c1-4615-9956-6e79c0fc780f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "50a57a20-d64c-478e-8764-9a3d9c1d437d",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Check Your Understanding",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Levels 5 and 6 are choice levels. Encourage students to try at least one and challenge themselves.\n\nThere is an optional activity guide available in the resource section for students to document their UMPIRE process as they work through today's coding challenges.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "50a57a20-d64c-478e-8764-9a3d9c1d437d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "87e468a2-14c1-4615-9956-6e79c0fc780f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "916962af-d2dd-4051-8ba0-fc1d48146c05",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As students work through the levels, walk around the room and look for common mistakes. Check whether students are remembering to use parentheses when calling functions. Watch for issues with indentation in their function definitions, which can cause errors in Python. Make sure the function names they are using to call functions match the ones they defined. If students get stuck, remind them to use the UMPIRE strategy to help plan and debug their code."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "916962af-d2dd-4051-8ba0-fc1d48146c05",
        "lesson_activity.key": "87e468a2-14c1-4615-9956-6e79c0fc780f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "dabaa32f-0bf4-4242-b7b7-5a95369d8877",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How is writing and calling a function in code similar to the function you created and acted out earlier?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize that both their acted-out function and a function written in code have a name that describes what the function does. They should understand that both include a specific sequence of steps that need to be followed in order. Students should also see that both types of functions can be reused simply by calling the name instead of repeating the steps.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students are struggling to make the connection between the unplugged activity and coding, refer back to one of the group-created functions. Ask the class to help \"translate\" it into Python by naming the function and describing what each step would look like in code. This can help students visualize how abstract actions become programmable instructions."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "dabaa32f-0bf4-4242-b7b7-5a95369d8877",
        "lesson_activity.key": "87e468a2-14c1-4615-9956-6e79c0fc780f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "57c965a8-b1a0-470b-b4ec-d0a5051c6a1e",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "57c965a8-b1a0-470b-b4ec-d0a5051c6a1e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "87e468a2-14c1-4615-9956-6e79c0fc780f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d7fa26c3-7251-422a-b269-266431da99a2",
      "position": 15,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Why is it helpful to include a comment in a function?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize that comments explain what a function is supposed to do without needing to read every line of code. They should also see comments as a way to communicate intent, especially when the function name alone doesn't tell the full story."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d7fa26c3-7251-422a-b269-266431da99a2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "87e468a2-14c1-4615-9956-6e79c0fc780f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6edcc5de-2cc7-4828-b423-de6821c0d7ab",
      "position": 16,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 6, Level 9 to complete Levels 9 through 12.\n- **Level #9:** Students complete a choice level where they write a function to replace repetitive code.\n- **Level #10:** Students complete a choice level where they define a function and call it multiple times.\n- **Level #11:** Students debug a broken program (missing parentheses, name mismatch).\n- **Level #12:** Students complete a Check Your Understanding.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Problem-Solving with Functions",
        "progression_name": "Problem-Solving with Functions"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6edcc5de-2cc7-4828-b423-de6821c0d7ab",
        "lesson_activity.key": "87e468a2-14c1-4615-9956-6e79c0fc780f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8e939a7d-1c96-43ae-9b0c-abcf594e2af7",
      "position": 17,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8e939a7d-1c96-43ae-9b0c-abcf594e2af7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "87e468a2-14c1-4615-9956-6e79c0fc780f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "65ebfd3e-423f-472a-a921-e6bee1045b1f",
      "position": 18,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As students work, support them in identifying common errors:\n- Is the function being called with the correct name?\n- Are they remembering to include parentheses when calling it?\n- Are there missing or misordered steps? Prompt students to revisit the UMPIRE strategy when they get stuck.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Levels 9 and 10 are choice levels. Encourage students to try at least one and challenge themselves.\n\nEncourage students to read error messages closely – they often point directly to the line with the issue. Remind them that debugging is part of being a programmer, and even small mistakes (like indentation or forgetting a colon) can break a function."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "65ebfd3e-423f-472a-a921-e6bee1045b1f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "87e468a2-14c1-4615-9956-6e79c0fc780f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b44268c7-2958-44d2-a794-6317132f589b",
      "position": 19,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b44268c7-2958-44d2-a794-6317132f589b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "87e468a2-14c1-4615-9956-6e79c0fc780f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7569aa19-0b04-4524-b2e7-61573c917d31",
      "position": 20,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What makes a function useful in a program?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should be able to explain that functions are useful in a program because they help organize code into meaningful chunks. Functions make code easier to read and understand, especially for other people (or for themselves later on). They also allow programmers to reuse code without having to rewrite it every time. Finally, functions make debugging and updating code easier because they isolate specific parts of the program."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7569aa19-0b04-4524-b2e7-61573c917d31",
        "lesson_activity.key": "87e468a2-14c1-4615-9956-6e79c0fc780f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2baceb21-23ff-4247-9228-daeb4e45b2f3",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students respond to the Question of the Day in their unit guides.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Key Vocabulary.",
        "name": "Question of the Day Reflection"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2baceb21-23ff-4247-9228-daeb4e45b2f3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "493bf096-cfa5-4800-86ca-9de8af778758"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "dcf6378f-cad1-4f80-ad64-d1f8170f3ab1",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What do you notice about these functions? Do we really need a separate function for each name?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize that the structure of each function is the same and only the name being greeted is changing. They may suggest that this is repetitive and could be simplified, setting up the need for parameters to make code more flexible and reusable.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How is using `say_hi(\"name\")` better than creating a different function for every person?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should understand that using a single function with a parameter is better than creating many separate functions because it reduces repetition in the code. They should also recognize that this approach makes the code shorter, easier to update, and more flexible. Ultimately, they should begin to see how parameters allow a single function to handle different inputs, which makes the function more reusable across different situations.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "dcf6378f-cad1-4f80-ad64-d1f8170f3ab1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "00bb911c-7c6e-4439-8827-74f93391bc9e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1d2c7df5-86c3-4842-a196-668191750c39",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Have students take out their Programming Fundamentals Unit Guide.\n\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *parameter*.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Parameters and Arguments",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Reinforce that a parameter only exists *inside* the function definition."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1d2c7df5-86c3-4842-a196-668191750c39",
        "lesson_activity.key": "451627c0-3379-4bcc-b51e-5ea6326e4982"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b611734d-4052-47de-8831-0e070cfc167a",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b611734d-4052-47de-8831-0e070cfc167a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "451627c0-3379-4bcc-b51e-5ea6326e4982"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fcb00a0c-6bc1-4fe1-8ff4-2662b06c7ae6",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What would be the parameter in this example?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should identify that the parameter is**name**– the placeholder inside the parentheses when the function is defined on line 1.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *argument*."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fcb00a0c-6bc1-4fe1-8ff4-2662b06c7ae6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "451627c0-3379-4bcc-b51e-5ea6326e4982"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ea5b02f2-21a5-4449-b2e1-573481e32693",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Think of the function like a fill-in-the-blank sentence. The parameter is the blank space, and the argument is the word you choose to put in.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ea5b02f2-21a5-4449-b2e1-573481e32693",
        "lesson_activity.key": "451627c0-3379-4bcc-b51e-5ea6326e4982"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3b975191-96e3-4a18-9921-1d561f2a4c36",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What about the argument?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize that `\"Taylor\"` is the argument — the actual value being passed into the function. They should understand that the argument replaces the parameter name when the function runs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the `takePaint()` method.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the `paint()` method. Be sure to point out the `color` parameter that lets the user choose what color the `Painter` uses.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain to students how to specify a color for the `Painter` to use. Emphasize that the color is written in quotes and passed as an argument to the `paint()` method."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3b975191-96e3-4a18-9921-1d561f2a4c36",
        "lesson_activity.key": "451627c0-3379-4bcc-b51e-5ea6326e4982"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "96465bde-56ce-42ca-a186-4fee239d4c99",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 7, Level 1 to complete Levels 1 through 6.\n- **Level #1:** In Python Lab, students complete a choice level where they add a parameter to a function.\n- **Level #2:** Students debug the missing argument.\n- **Level #3:** Students debug wrong parameter name and parameter trying to be used outside of function.\n- **Level #4:** Students complete a choice level where they explore using `take_paint()` and `paint()`.\n- **Level #5:** Students complete a choice level where they add a `Painter` parameter.\n- **Level #6:** Students complete a Check Your Understanding.",
        "progression_name": "Parameters and Arguments"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "96465bde-56ce-42ca-a186-4fee239d4c99",
        "lesson_activity.key": "451627c0-3379-4bcc-b51e-5ea6326e4982"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "55018e28-c87e-4f3e-a085-0e33ea4e78e9",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "55018e28-c87e-4f3e-a085-0e33ea4e78e9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "451627c0-3379-4bcc-b51e-5ea6326e4982"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b77f273f-84bc-4b1c-92c4-72d0e81dfe43",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Check Your Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b77f273f-84bc-4b1c-92c4-72d0e81dfe43",
        "lesson_activity.key": "451627c0-3379-4bcc-b51e-5ea6326e4982"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "416591e5-0b6a-4642-bd16-37fbcb6e36e1",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As students work through the levels, circulate around the room to check for understanding. Listen for students using the terms parameter and argument correctly, and ask them to explain the difference in their own words if needed. Watch for common debugging issues, such as missing quotation marks around strings or calling functions with the wrong number of arguments. This is also a great opportunity to highlight when students successfully use a parameter to make their function more flexible or reusable – point it out and encourage them to share their thinking with a partner.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Levels 1, 4, and 5 are choice levels. Encourage students to try at least one and challenge themselves.\n\nThere is an optional activity guide available in the resource section for students to document their UMPIRE process.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "416591e5-0b6a-4642-bd16-37fbcb6e36e1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "451627c0-3379-4bcc-b51e-5ea6326e4982"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8d095d7c-c375-41ba-ae87-f278a88d7cbf",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8d095d7c-c375-41ba-ae87-f278a88d7cbf",
        "lesson_activity.key": "451627c0-3379-4bcc-b51e-5ea6326e4982"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e25d2160-44db-42a0-be00-adadc4b2fb16",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Do This: Click through the animated slide to explain the difference between function and method.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain why parameters are useful for functions.",
        "duration": "20",
        "name": "Painter Functions"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e25d2160-44db-42a0-be00-adadc4b2fb16",
        "lesson_activity.key": "451627c0-3379-4bcc-b51e-5ea6326e4982"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3bf0c6dd-2aab-480d-874c-fcb2c7c7a614",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "A module is just a regular Python file. By storing your functions in a module like custom.py, you can keep your code organized and avoid repeating yourself. Then, when you want to use those functions in your main program, you just import them.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3bf0c6dd-2aab-480d-874c-fcb2c7c7a614",
        "lesson_activity.key": "451627c0-3379-4bcc-b51e-5ea6326e4982"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b235ec0b-7257-415c-8d2a-2c4b7a2c443a",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *module*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Walk through the code examples on both sides of the screen. Start with the file labeled `custom.py`, and explain that this file is used to define your functions — in this case, a simple `greet()` function that prints `\"Hello, World!\"` Then move to the file labeled `main.py`. Explain that this is the file where you actually use or call the function.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Emphasize that one file defines the function, and the other file uses it. If students understand this relationship now, they'll be more successful when managing larger projects later on."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b235ec0b-7257-415c-8d2a-2c4b7a2c443a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "451627c0-3379-4bcc-b51e-5ea6326e4982"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8242a49d-b0ef-421a-8735-ac06f4e324ca",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8242a49d-b0ef-421a-8735-ac06f4e324ca",
        "lesson_activity.key": "451627c0-3379-4bcc-b51e-5ea6326e4982"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0189781b-2b83-4f0c-85d9-1b93a18ef58e",
      "position": 15,
      "properties": {
        "description": "The Backpack is a tool that lets you save your Python files, like**custom.py**, so you can use them again in a different program. This is super helpful when you've written a great helper function and want to keep it for future projects. Think of it as a personal storage space for your best code.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0189781b-2b83-4f0c-85d9-1b93a18ef58e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "451627c0-3379-4bcc-b51e-5ea6326e4982"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1278d379-3fd9-4a34-9868-6eb6894bab74",
      "position": 16,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that the Backpack is a way to save work they want to reuse later, especially custom helper functions they've written.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Reinforce UMPIRE as a step-by-step strategy that students can use whenever they are writing a function.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "UMPIRE is especially helpful for students who feel stuck getting started or overwhelmed by function structure. Refer back to this strategy during coding time to support students in working independently.\n\nShare the following strategy steps with your students if they need a reminder for how to implement UMPIRE with a programming task:\n- **Understand:** Define or restate the problem\n- **Make a Plan:** Ideas for solving the problem - could involve writing pseudocode or using computational thinking strategies\n- **Produce:** Write your code!\n- **Inspect:** Trace and test your code as you develop it. Ask for feedback, as necessary\n- **Refine:** Iterate your design until it meets your criteria\n- **Explain:** Talk though your code, your choices, or your process with a peer\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1278d379-3fd9-4a34-9868-6eb6894bab74",
        "lesson_activity.key": "451627c0-3379-4bcc-b51e-5ea6326e4982"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9d90f151-618d-446d-b614-45828920456b",
      "position": 17,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9d90f151-618d-446d-b614-45828920456b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "451627c0-3379-4bcc-b51e-5ea6326e4982"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0f1461bb-0676-4e9f-b0a1-37a4596abbfb",
      "position": 18,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 6, Level 9 to complete Levels 9 through 11.\n- **Level #7:** Students complete a choice level where they write and use a `turn_right()` function.\n- **Level #8:** Students debug broken `custom.py` and `main.py` files.\n- **Level #9:** Students complete a choice level where they write and use a new function.\n- **Level #10:** Students complete a vocabulary Check Your Understanding.\n- **Level #11:** Students complete a Check Your Understanding.",
        "progression_name": "Painter Functions"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0f1461bb-0676-4e9f-b0a1-37a4596abbfb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "451627c0-3379-4bcc-b51e-5ea6326e4982"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "46e82856-c6c1-4536-a586-fb4f7b6cbd06",
      "position": 19,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As students work, support them by asking clarifying questions about their function structure. Prompt them to check file names, imports, and syntax when debugging. Celebrate when students reuse functions or take a creative approach to painting designs.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Levels 10 and 11 are choice levels. Encourage students to try at least one and challenge themselves.\n\nEncourage students to use a debugging checklist as they work:\n- Is the function name the same in both files?\n- Did you call the function with parentheses?\n- Did you import it correctly?"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "46e82856-c6c1-4536-a586-fb4f7b6cbd06",
        "lesson_activity.key": "451627c0-3379-4bcc-b51e-5ea6326e4982"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6bca21c8-4915-48ae-802d-61b3dd36be0b",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students respond to the Question of the Day in their unit guides.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Key Vocabulary.",
        "name": "Question of the Day Reflection"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6bca21c8-4915-48ae-802d-61b3dd36be0b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d8af7371-e5e1-4e7c-9841-a356e8b0b36e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "43ccf1c0-83b3-4b4f-9764-03a2214b7093",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Before students arrive, scatter small items (e.g., markers, paper clips, sticky notes) around the room and designate a cardboard box or plastic bin as the place for the items to end up. Tell students to read the prompt on the screen and follow the directions.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *What was the condition for repeating the task?*\n- *What made the task stop?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should understand that the condition was “items on the floor”. While this was still true, students needed to continue picking up the items and placing them in the bin. They stopped the task when all of the items had been collected.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Remind students of the definition and components of an algorithm.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "name": "Repeating Tasks"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "43ccf1c0-83b3-4b4f-9764-03a2214b7093",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3925fb2a-1959-46f1-a322-7ce96f3e84a1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "276c83f9-0a2c-4967-9b08-4ecc18c8e983",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Have students take out their Programming Fundamentals Unit Guide.\n\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Suppose we wanted to move our `Painter` from (0,0) to the edge of The Neighborhood. Why might we want to reduce repetition?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize that typing the same line of code over and over is repetitive, inefficient, and easy to mess up. They might say things like, \"This takes a lot of space,\" or \"If I wanted to change something, I'd have to change it in every line,\" or \"It’s boring to write.\" This sets up the motivation for using a loop – to make code shorter, cleaner, and easier to manage.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Introduction to while Loops",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Jot down some of the student responses on the board. Highlight any comments about efficiency, readability, or avoiding mistakes – those will be key ideas to return to when you introduce the loop syntax next."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "276c83f9-0a2c-4967-9b08-4ecc18c8e983",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b3b84662-5ead-4fdc-b5f0-41dc794fd539"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "48aaa5d7-0fa7-471d-8570-d461ad70987c",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "48aaa5d7-0fa7-471d-8570-d461ad70987c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b3b84662-5ead-4fdc-b5f0-41dc794fd539"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "be641172-1614-46c9-9fb2-139f517fc1c5",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Point to the code snippet on the slide. Highlight that this code does the exact same thing as the repeated `talia.move()` lines from the previous slide – but it's shorter, cleaner, and easier to understand. Explain the structure of the `while` loop: the keyword `while`, the condition `talia.canMove()`, the colon `:`, and the indented action `talia.move()`.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "This is a good moment to explicitly connect students' earlier observations to this code. Ask them if this matches what they saw the robot doing in the unplugged activity – repeating an action until a stop condition was met."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "be641172-1614-46c9-9fb2-139f517fc1c5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b3b84662-5ead-4fdc-b5f0-41dc794fd539"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bf602b4a-cce0-45c3-8bc8-f32dba72fe0d",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bf602b4a-cce0-45c3-8bc8-f32dba72fe0d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b3b84662-5ead-4fdc-b5f0-41dc794fd539"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "196e748a-995c-463f-860c-78472fa468fd",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This: ** Define*loop*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that `while` is a keyword in Python that signals the start of a loop. This tells the computer to repeat something while a condition is true.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Let students know that keywords like while are special — they're built into the language and always need to be spelled exactly right. If a keyword is misspelled, the program won't run."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "196e748a-995c-463f-860c-78472fa468fd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b3b84662-5ead-4fdc-b5f0-41dc794fd539"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "74d7fd9c-8129-40ff-a8f7-a137da007ab0",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "74d7fd9c-8129-40ff-a8f7-a137da007ab0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b3b84662-5ead-4fdc-b5f0-41dc794fd539"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b0eeeef5-d4fc-40a4-924d-89d40fd8378f",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that `talia.can_move()` is what the computer checks before running the loop. If it's true, the loop runs. If it's false, the loop ends.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Help students understand that what is checked must always give a Boolean value (`True` or `False`). You might ask the class: \"What else might we check in a loop?\""
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b0eeeef5-d4fc-40a4-924d-89d40fd8378f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b3b84662-5ead-4fdc-b5f0-41dc794fd539"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "15ceb439-02e4-4b7a-bc94-aa54bd8c7105",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "15ceb439-02e4-4b7a-bc94-aa54bd8c7105",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b3b84662-5ead-4fdc-b5f0-41dc794fd539"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "103739cb-48ff-4a6e-9cfd-4dfa25205b55",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that the colon is required syntax and tells Python that the next indented lines belong to the loop.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that this block is the part of the code that runs again and again while the condition is true.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Use this slide to reinforce the visual structure of the loop. Ask students what they notice about the spacing in front of the two lines that run inside the loop.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Remind students that indentation matters in Python. Without it, the computer won't know what code is part of the loop. If a line is not indented, it won't repeat!"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "103739cb-48ff-4a6e-9cfd-4dfa25205b55",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b3b84662-5ead-4fdc-b5f0-41dc794fd539"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ca0d189a-ee59-4937-a7e6-f03c1f70cda8",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ca0d189a-ee59-4937-a7e6-f03c1f70cda8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b3b84662-5ead-4fdc-b5f0-41dc794fd539"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "58cc06e7-d446-4252-88ea-d7585006ef56",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain how a `while` loop works. Walk students through the flowchart:\n- The program checks the condition (`talia.canMove()`).\n- If it's `True`, the action (`talia.move()`) happens.\n- Then it checks the condition again.\n- If it's still `True`, it repeats. If it's `False`, the loop ends.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *condition*."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "58cc06e7-d446-4252-88ea-d7585006ef56",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b3b84662-5ead-4fdc-b5f0-41dc794fd539"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bf0348e9-f089-445a-af7c-82dc66a62e6a",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Today, we will work with three new methods that give our `Painter` information in the form of either true or false, also called a Boolean value.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bf0348e9-f089-445a-af7c-82dc66a62e6a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b3b84662-5ead-4fdc-b5f0-41dc794fd539"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d1111c87-cd59-47a0-999a-b2f8be02e5f1",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 8, Level 1 to complete Levels 1 through 6.\n- **Level #1:** In Python Lab, students modify code using `can_move()` in a `while` loop.\n- **Level #2:** Students modify code using `has_paint()` in a `while` loop.\n- **Level #3:** Students modify code using `is_on_bucket()` in a `while` loop.\n- **Level #4:** Students debug a `while` loop that has an indentation error.\n- **Level #5:** Students are given a loop like `while painter.has_paint():` but the `Painter` starts without paint. They observe that the loop doesn't run and must fix the condition.\n- **Level #6:** Students complete a Check Your Understanding.",
        "progression_name": "Exploring while Loops"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d1111c87-cd59-47a0-999a-b2f8be02e5f1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b3b84662-5ead-4fdc-b5f0-41dc794fd539"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0f7a7ed3-fb87-4d49-903a-cf4518d5200c",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Check Your Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0f7a7ed3-fb87-4d49-903a-cf4518d5200c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b3b84662-5ead-4fdc-b5f0-41dc794fd539"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1797a7d6-fb76-4eef-a8de-e9f662b4a117",
      "position": 15,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As students work, look for:\n- Whether they understand the loop structure (condition, colon, indented block)\n- Misconceptions about when the loop should stop",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to say what their loop is doing in plain language before writing it in code. This helps them think through the logic before jumping into syntax."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1797a7d6-fb76-4eef-a8de-e9f662b4a117",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b3b84662-5ead-4fdc-b5f0-41dc794fd539"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "66ffe2b4-dece-4f7f-8a25-fea749ac1b80",
      "position": 16,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "66ffe2b4-dece-4f7f-8a25-fea749ac1b80",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b3b84662-5ead-4fdc-b5f0-41dc794fd539"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "21afbf6a-7141-4d87-84a9-fecb21f0c96c",
      "position": 17,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What did you learn about `while` loops?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should share what they noticed about `while` loops, such as the syntax or how they are used to repeat actions.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What questions do you still have about `while` loops?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should share any questions they have about `while` loops.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What are the benefits of using while loops in your code?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize that `while` loops are useful because they reduce repetition in code and make programs shorter and easier to read. They should understand that `while` loops allow the computer to repeat an action over and over until a condition becomes false. This is especially helpful when we don't know in advance how many times an action needs to happen. Some students may also point out that loops make it easier to debug or update code, since you don't have to change the same instruction in multiple places – those are excellent insights to highlight and build on.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 8, Level 7 to complete Levels 7 through 10.\n- **Level #7:** Students complete a choice level where they write a function that uses `can_move()`.\n- **Level #8:** Students write a function that uses `is_on_bucket()`.\n- **Level #9:** Students complete a choice level where they write a function that uses `has_paint()`.\n- **Level #10:** Students complete a vocabulary Check Your Understanding.\n- **Level #11:** Students complete a Check Your Understanding.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Loops with the Painter",
        "progression_name": "Loops with the Painter",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Levels 7 and 9 are choice levels. Encourage students to try at least one and challenge themselves.\n\nEncourage students to use the UMPIRE strategy as they work through each level: plan what the loop should do, identify the stopping condition, write the code, test it, revise it, and explain how it works."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "21afbf6a-7141-4d87-84a9-fecb21f0c96c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b3b84662-5ead-4fdc-b5f0-41dc794fd539"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bffb9020-a4cd-42e0-bc1b-8565f07e18ec",
      "position": 18,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As students work, watch for whether they're correctly using indentation and syntax and if they're thinking through when the loop should stop. Ask students to explain their loop in plain language if they're stuck — that often helps them catch logic errors or infinite loop mistakes."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bffb9020-a4cd-42e0-bc1b-8565f07e18ec",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b3b84662-5ead-4fdc-b5f0-41dc794fd539"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4d651f42-313b-41d8-b9f9-b79d677de91d",
      "position": 19,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4d651f42-313b-41d8-b9f9-b79d677de91d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b3b84662-5ead-4fdc-b5f0-41dc794fd539"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a57f25d8-4c1a-4df6-b394-4cfb08ed206f",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students respond to the Question of the Day in their unit guides.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Key Vocabulary.",
        "name": "Question of the Day Reflection"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a57f25d8-4c1a-4df6-b394-4cfb08ed206f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2e00f3e2-2d47-41ae-b552-856a5536591c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "26cd2bd4-28e4-400b-b3e7-1240a66b4aaa",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain the instructions of the quick selection game. Students will listen to a description you give and then stand if it fits them. Pause and discuss after each instruction and ask a student who didn't stand to explain why. Here are a few descriptions to get the game started:\n- If you are wearing black, stand up.\n- If you are wearing jewelry, stand up.\n- If your name begins with the letter M or J.",
        "name": "Yes or No",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Each class will most likely use different conditions due to the uniqueness and variety of students, dress codes, etc. You may need to change these scenarios based on the makeup of your unique class and students. You can also change the conditions with each instruction and add more instructions to involve more students and if you have time."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "26cd2bd4-28e4-400b-b3e7-1240a66b4aaa",
        "lesson_activity.key": "261aa67b-5145-4596-b5ea-66ccd93d22b6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3073164e-b3e1-467a-b243-4d3489d30e2c",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3073164e-b3e1-467a-b243-4d3489d30e2c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "261aa67b-5145-4596-b5ea-66ccd93d22b6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "59c85e10-3a8f-4d51-bc28-9b79cda72616",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Remind students of the definition and components of an algorithm.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Which component of an algorithm did you just experience when you either stood or stayed seated?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should realize that they demonstrate selection.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "59c85e10-3a8f-4d51-bc28-9b79cda72616",
        "lesson_activity.key": "261aa67b-5145-4596-b5ea-66ccd93d22b6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3ca5a9a4-4756-4d79-a204-409300ae2ba1",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Give students a moment to think about what the program will do. Have students discuss their predictions with a partner. Then have a few students share their predictions.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Introduction to if Statements",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Let the students know that they can assume a `Painter` object called `isabel` has been created and that it has taken paint from the bucket."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3ca5a9a4-4756-4d79-a204-409300ae2ba1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "346ae51d-5249-4a34-93bb-769546b27d35"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "41dad291-5f1f-4e8c-80fe-29be9279f997",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "41dad291-5f1f-4e8c-80fe-29be9279f997",
        "lesson_activity.key": "346ae51d-5249-4a34-93bb-769546b27d35"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "43fedf26-56b0-4607-99d4-4a8a0160d3c1",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students compare what they predicted would happen to what they see happening. If their prediction differed from the actual output, ask them to reflect on why that is.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students should notice that the program contains two identical `if` statements. Both `if` statements check if the `Painter` can move south, but only the first one evaluates to `True`. This is because once the `Painter` takes a step forward it can no longer move south. As a result, the second `if` statement evaluates to `False` and that entire chunk of code is skipped."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "43fedf26-56b0-4607-99d4-4a8a0160d3c1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "346ae51d-5249-4a34-93bb-769546b27d35"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3bac3ba1-1093-4a75-8f25-9baa462bf0bc",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Have students take out their Programming Fundamentals Unit Guide.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3bac3ba1-1093-4a75-8f25-9baa462bf0bc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "346ae51d-5249-4a34-93bb-769546b27d35"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ca7c07ae-f729-45c2-8722-89d2a1edcd25",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *conditional statement*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that the word if tells the computer to check something – a condition – and only run the next steps if that condition is true.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that this is the condition. If it is true, then the steps that follow will run.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that the colon tells Python that the next indented lines are part of the `if` block.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that these lines will only run if the condition is true.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Remind students that indentation is important in Python. Emphasize that if these lines weren't indented, they would always run, even if the condition were false.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Why do you think conditionals are useful in programs? What kinds of decisions might a program need to make?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should connect conditionals to decision-making like checking for input (e.g., \"Did the user click a button?\"), avoiding errors (e.g., \"Can the character move?\"), or controlling flow based on conditions (e.g., \"If a variable reaches 10, reset the game.\").\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 9, Level 1 to complete Levels 1 through 5.\n- **Level #1:** In Python Lab, students modify the code so that the Painter paints only if it is facing west.\n- **Level #2:** Students modify the code so that the the Painter turns right if it can move south.\n- **Level #3:** Students write an if statement that makes the Painter turn right if it is on paint.\n- **Level #4:** Students debug indentation errors and syntax errors.\n- **Level #5:** Students complete a Check Your Understanding.",
        "progression_name": "Exploring Conditionals"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ca7c07ae-f729-45c2-8722-89d2a1edcd25",
        "lesson_activity.key": "346ae51d-5249-4a34-93bb-769546b27d35"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c0542057-c942-4b5a-b91e-198cee0abbae",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Check Your Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c0542057-c942-4b5a-b91e-198cee0abbae",
        "lesson_activity.key": "346ae51d-5249-4a34-93bb-769546b27d35"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "406bbbae-1226-4e6c-ace3-157c23af92c5",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Watch for students struggling with forgetting colons or indentation, understanding how the `Painter`'s direction affects behavior, and reading the problem carefully to choose the correct condition."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "406bbbae-1226-4e6c-ace3-157c23af92c5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "346ae51d-5249-4a34-93bb-769546b27d35"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "376e3b00-4489-471a-b059-c10d6497ce77",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What did you learn about `if` statements?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should mention that `if` runs code only when the condition is true and note the importance of indentation.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What questions do you still have about `if` statements?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should share any questions they have. These might be questions like \"When do I need a colon?\" or \"What happens when the condition is false?\"\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What are the benefits of using `if` statements in our code?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should share how programs make decisions, prevent unwanted actions, and make their code more flexible and dynamic.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Remind students to use to the UMPIRE strategy as they work through the following choice levels.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Decisions with the Painter",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "There is an optional activity guide available in the resource section for students to document their UMPIRE process as they work through today's coding challenges.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "376e3b00-4489-471a-b059-c10d6497ce77",
        "lesson_activity.key": "346ae51d-5249-4a34-93bb-769546b27d35"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ef6fcb18-665d-41d3-b426-66757294ed6e",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 9, Level 6 to complete Levels 6 through 9.\n- **Level #6:** Students complete a choice level where they modify the code to use an `if` statement inside a `while` loop.\n- **Level #7:** Students complete a choice level using `while` and `if` statements in The Neighborhood.\n- **Level #8:** Students complete a vocabulary Check Your Understanding.\n- **Level #9:** Students complete a Check Your Understanding.",
        "progression_name": "Decisions with the Painter"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ef6fcb18-665d-41d3-b426-66757294ed6e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "346ae51d-5249-4a34-93bb-769546b27d35"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "91dc411f-6bee-4a86-95cd-f264d4ee11d9",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Notice how students apply what they learned in new contexts with The Neighborhood.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Levels 6 and 7 are choice levels. Encourage students to try at least one and challenge themselves.\n\nEncourage students to plan their logic before coding. Ask \"What do you want the `Painter` to check for?\""
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "91dc411f-6bee-4a86-95cd-f264d4ee11d9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "346ae51d-5249-4a34-93bb-769546b27d35"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "54e033cc-1e71-4bb7-ad15-2d768898d0cf",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students respond to the Question of the Day in their unit guides.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Key Vocabulary.",
        "name": "Question of the Day Reflection"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "54e033cc-1e71-4bb7-ad15-2d768898d0cf",
        "lesson_activity.key": "60cc9360-61fe-4f19-a480-c85b63164f4b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a615ea95-7a8b-4118-a527-210defbbcb88",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a615ea95-7a8b-4118-a527-210defbbcb88",
        "lesson_activity.key": "df021991-accd-4b9c-8e2f-221c729b3f54"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1932f829-3020-4617-b413-a3a46b1cec93",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *What apps do you use every day?*\n- *What kind of general algorithms do they use to solve problems for you?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize that many apps rely on algorithms to solve problems and make decisions, often without users realizing it. They should begin making connections between common apps and the types of algorithms they use, such as recommendation systems, search ranking, and navigation. Listen for examples that show an understanding of how algorithms influence daily experiences, such as streaming services suggesting content, navigation apps calculating routes, or shopping apps recommending products.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that they have been writing algorithms to navigate our Painter around the Neighborhood, but today, they are going to explore how algorithms work in real-world apps and how their design can impact users like you and me.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1932f829-3020-4617-b413-a3a46b1cec93",
        "lesson_activity.key": "df021991-accd-4b9c-8e2f-221c729b3f54"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "154b669b-7c96-4524-816d-1da7e25a292a",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Put students into groups of two.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair of students the Algorithm Decision-Making activity guide. Or direct them to Level 1 to complete the Activity Guide on their device.\n\n",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Debugging a Music Selection Algorithm",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Decide in advance if you want to print out the Activity Guide for students or have them complete it digitally."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "154b669b-7c96-4524-816d-1da7e25a292a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "402be37a-a02b-4e89-91db-4fa2b0fd766b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3fd3a870-dac1-4554-818c-b41a32469854",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to complete Part 1 of their activity guide where they analyze a flawed music selection algorithm using a flowchart, identify what the algorithm currently does, its limitations, and possible improvements. Guide them to focus on how the algorithm makes recommendations and whether it considers diverse user preferences. Clarify that this is an analysis activity, not about finding a single correct answer.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As students work, listen for discussions identifying the algorithm’s behavior, such as only recommending songs from the first selected genre. Look for students recognizing limitations like lack of diversity or bias toward initial choices. Encourage creative improvement ideas, such as incorporating recent searches or expanding recommendations over time. ",
        "progression_name": "Algorithms IRL",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage them to think critically about how the algorithm makes decisions and how it could be more effective. Emphasize that there are no wrong answers—the goal is to develop problem-solving skills and consider the broader impact of algorithmic choices."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3fd3a870-dac1-4554-818c-b41a32469854",
        "lesson_activity.key": "402be37a-a02b-4e89-91db-4fa2b0fd766b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "dacd6642-fb6f-4897-a200-8cb80664ecf7",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "dacd6642-fb6f-4897-a200-8cb80664ecf7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "402be37a-a02b-4e89-91db-4fa2b0fd766b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "68767580-36a0-41e5-b399-b2374f09acdd",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Play the music clip to cue the Give One, Get One activity and direct students to participate in a Give One, Get One to share their ideas for proposed solutions.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Using music to cue transitions helps create routines in the classroom. When students hear cues, they know it is time to transition to a specific activity. Emphasize to students what the music clip means, and be consistent with the use of the music clip to cue the activity. Click the blue play icon on the slide to play the music cue.\n\nGive One, Get One encourages students to seek and share ideas and information. Students circulate the classroom and pair up with a partner when prompted by the teacher. Each student \"gives\" or shares one of their ideas as the other student \"gets\" or listens and writes it down. The teacher then prompts students to find new partners and repeat the process."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "68767580-36a0-41e5-b399-b2374f09acdd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "402be37a-a02b-4e89-91db-4fa2b0fd766b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "38405927-030d-4242-9cf3-c2a3c51c4faf",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "38405927-030d-4242-9cf3-c2a3c51c4faf",
        "lesson_activity.key": "402be37a-a02b-4e89-91db-4fa2b0fd766b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fa5aaeb2-cf8e-4c97-8f62-58846c6032d9",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *What similarities do you see across these suggestions?*\n- *What challenges might arise when implementing these improvements?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize common themes in their proposed improvements, such as increasing variety in recommendations or considering user feedback. They should also discuss challenges like balancing personalization with diversity or ensuring the algorithm adapts over time. "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fa5aaeb2-cf8e-4c97-8f62-58846c6032d9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "402be37a-a02b-4e89-91db-4fa2b0fd766b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c534b9ce-dcc1-4437-b070-ddef4f0a6650",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Have students take out their Programming Fundamentals Unit Guide.\n\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the key term *bias*. Have students add an example, an image, or a connection that would help them makes sense of the work in their unit guide.  \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the key term *ethics*. Have students add an example, an image, or a connection that would help them makes sense of the work in their unit guide.  ",
        "duration": "20",
        "name": "Ethical Exploration of Autonomous Vehicle Algorithms"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c534b9ce-dcc1-4437-b070-ddef4f0a6650",
        "lesson_activity.key": "402be37a-a02b-4e89-91db-4fa2b0fd766b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b6fbfab7-f252-4b89-99f9-2c5ad10c9ec0",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Show students the Waymo Self-Driving GIF to demonstrate a real-life autonomous vehicle swerving to avoid a pedestrian. Use this example to highlight how real-world AI must make split-second ethical decisions and how different scenarios could lead to different outcomes.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *How do the music algorithm and self-driving car algorithm affect people’s lives?*\n- *How can we make these algorithms more fair?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should make a connection between the music algorithm and self-driving car algorithm as two ways that humans are affected by AI-powered algorithms. The software engineers who created these algorithms made certain decisions for the AI to take, such as what genre of music to recommend or what to have the car do if a pedestrian unexpectedly runs into the road. Encourage students to continue thinking of real-world decisions that are made by AI algorithms."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b6fbfab7-f252-4b89-99f9-2c5ad10c9ec0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "402be37a-a02b-4e89-91db-4fa2b0fd766b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4a284003-bb8b-4512-b4a8-29bb75994f3b",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to complete Part 2 of their activity guide where they analyze the self-driving car decision-making algorithm by identifying what it does, the factors it considers, the trade-offs involved, and who benefits or is harmed. Encourage them to think critically about the algorithm’s priorities and limitations. Remind them that real-world algorithms must balance multiple factors, often leading to ethical dilemmas.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As students work, listen for discussions identifying the algorithm’s steps, such as detecting obstacles, assessing risks, and making a decision. Look for students recognizing the factors considered, like pedestrian safety, passenger safety, and legal concerns. Encourage analysis of trade-offs, such as whether avoiding one accident increases the risk of another. Pay attention to conversations about ethical implications, including who benefits, who is at risk, and what makes a decision \"fair.\" "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4a284003-bb8b-4512-b4a8-29bb75994f3b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "402be37a-a02b-4e89-91db-4fa2b0fd766b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "af9e26e2-e273-4b50-a5b7-9f89880eefa2",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We’ve been using the UMPIRE strategy to help us write code for our programs. But remember, this strategy can be used any time we are faced with a problem or a task that we need to work through. ",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "af9e26e2-e273-4b50-a5b7-9f89880eefa2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "402be37a-a02b-4e89-91db-4fa2b0fd766b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f2044b39-c055-441e-baf7-842e6a889312",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the first three steps of the UMPIRE strategy in the context of a general task or problem to be solved. "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f2044b39-c055-441e-baf7-842e6a889312",
        "lesson_activity.key": "402be37a-a02b-4e89-91db-4fa2b0fd766b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d270cde4-71b9-4ac4-bae2-d656773df516",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** With their partners, have students examine the presented scenarios involving self-driving cars within the activity guide. Students should examine each scenario and describe the considerations that they would have to make in order to have their algorithm respond to the scenarios.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As students work, ask guiding questions like, “What criteria would you prioritize?” to deepen student thinking. Encourage discussion among partners by prompting students to consider whether there is a \"right\" decision or if it depends on the situation. Connect the discussion to real-world AI challenges, highlighting how autonomous vehicles must make split-second ethical decisions with real consequences.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d270cde4-71b9-4ac4-bae2-d656773df516",
        "lesson_activity.key": "402be37a-a02b-4e89-91db-4fa2b0fd766b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e77d4040-cb9b-4979-990b-71661c2e3afd",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now that you've had the opportunity to understand the problem that self-driving cars face and to plan and produce a solution, let's share those ideas with your classmates in order to get some ideas on how we might refine our algorithms.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e77d4040-cb9b-4979-990b-71661c2e3afd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "402be37a-a02b-4e89-91db-4fa2b0fd766b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "03758859-7bdf-437a-a95f-53c9c409a20f",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the final three steps of the UMPIRE strategy in the context of a general task or problem to be solved. "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "03758859-7bdf-437a-a95f-53c9c409a20f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "402be37a-a02b-4e89-91db-4fa2b0fd766b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e4acef8c-6a13-4960-9564-be43fbfe2362",
      "position": 15,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share some of their ideas that they produced for how to update the algorithms for the self-driving car hypothetical scenarios.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e4acef8c-6a13-4960-9564-be43fbfe2362",
        "lesson_activity.key": "402be37a-a02b-4e89-91db-4fa2b0fd766b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "50c3b7a9-f9dc-4106-b3f6-ff71fd573ca9",
      "position": 16,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "50c3b7a9-f9dc-4106-b3f6-ff71fd573ca9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "402be37a-a02b-4e89-91db-4fa2b0fd766b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5da7bd5c-6cb8-4d17-8078-4ac3d4c124e0",
      "position": 17,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *How did using the UMPIRE strategy help you design a fair and balanced algorithm?*\n- *How does public trust in autonomous systems depend on ethical decision-making?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize the challenges of designing decision-making algorithms that balance fairness, ethics, and functionality, and how using a strategy such as UMPIRE can help with these challenges. Students should also recognize how these challenges impact public trust in autonomous systems. Listen for students identifying trade-offs in algorithmic decisions, such as prioritizing safety vs. efficiency, and discussing how bias, transparency, or accountability affect trust in AI systems.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to consider multiple perspectives by asking follow-up questions like, \"Who benefits from this decision? Who might be harmed?\" or \"How would you feel if you were affected by this algorithm?\" If students focus only on technical challenges, prompt them to think about ethics and public trust by asking, \"Would people trust a system that makes decisions without transparency?\" Remind students that there are no perfect answers—the goal is to explore trade-offs in algorithmic decision-making."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "Activity guides can be collected and used to formatively assess the objectives:\n- Analyze the role of algorithms in apps to solve real-world problems.\n- Debug an algorithm and propose changes to improve functionality for diverse users.\n- Evaluate ethical implications of algorithmic decision-making."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5da7bd5c-6cb8-4d17-8078-4ac3d4c124e0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "402be37a-a02b-4e89-91db-4fa2b0fd766b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "229d7187-ce33-4bd9-99e6-98d0fe4a44dd",
      "position": 18,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Student Survey"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "229d7187-ce33-4bd9-99e6-98d0fe4a44dd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "402be37a-a02b-4e89-91db-4fa2b0fd766b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "50f760db-db17-405d-b0d1-356d832295a1",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Instruct students to write their responses to the question of the day in their Unit Guide. After a moment, click the slide to display a helpful hint for how students can think about this question in the context of their experiences today. After 2–3 minutes, facilitate a quick sharing activity (e.g., Whip Around or Popcorn Share), calling on a few students to share their ideas.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The question of the day in the Unit Guide can be used to assess the lesson objectives. Look for depth of understanding in how students connect algorithmic decision-making to real-world impact and ethical considerations. Specifically, they should check for:\n- **Examples of how algorithms impact daily life** – Does the student mention real-world applications like recommendation systems, self-driving cars, or hiring algorithms?\n- **Recognition of ethical challenges** – Does the student acknowledge issues like bias, fairness, or unintended consequences in algorithm design?\n- **Consideration of trade-offs** – Does the student discuss how programmers must balance accuracy, efficiency, and ethical responsibility when designing algorithms?\n- **A thoughtful perspective on responsible algorithm design** – Does the student suggest ways to make algorithms more fair, transparent, or trustworthy?"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "50f760db-db17-405d-b0d1-356d832295a1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "336827a9-e058-4e58-bdab-ce5b94395963"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "692992ef-8c7a-4b84-be63-174a2b02f34a",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Remind students that earlier in the unit, they explored the pillars of computational thinking—Decomposition, Pattern Recognition, Abstraction, and Algorithm Design—to solve programming challenges. Explain that today's lesson focuses on decomposition, breaking a problem into smaller steps to make it easier to solve. Ask students what they remember about these pillars and encourage them to share examples of when they used them in previous lessons. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How have you used decomposition - breaking problems down into smaller steps - throughout your work in this unit or outside of school?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize how decomposition helps break down complex tasks into smaller, more manageable steps, both in programming and everyday problem-solving. Listen for responses that describe breaking tasks into steps, such as planning a coding project, organizing a school assignment, or learning a new skill.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the learning objectives.\n\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "692992ef-8c7a-4b84-be63-174a2b02f34a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4e70abbc-29a8-4aa1-b9d1-c06a5867c984"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6233eb7b-dedb-4ae0-a90c-c1429956de61",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students discuss with a partner: What patterns do you see in the image? Encourage them to look for repeated shapes, colors, or layout elements.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** After pairs have discussed, ask for a few volunteers to share out. Then click through the slide to reveal the example patterns: Purple Lines, Black Squares, Blue Squares.",
        "name": "Decomposing an Image Example",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students are unsure where to start, prompt them to describe one row or one column and look for what repeats. Suggest tracing or counting colors to spot repetition more easily."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6233eb7b-dedb-4ae0-a90c-c1429956de61",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5c817be-275f-4e82-9148-4e3fbab7008e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "52d6a686-51cc-4e46-b610-1509ddb9f01a",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Ask students to discuss with a partner: If we wanted to code this image, what functions could we create based on the patterns we just noticed?\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** After discussion, call on a few students to share their ideas. Then click to reveal the sample function names: `purple_line()`, `black_square()`, `blue_square()`.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to use function names that describe the outcome of the pattern. If students suggest vague names like do_it(), push them to explain what the function actually does."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "52d6a686-51cc-4e46-b610-1509ddb9f01a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5c817be-275f-4e82-9148-4e3fbab7008e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0abe1eb7-3e7f-4288-9d0c-8ebc0f028f87",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students talk with a partner about what pseudocode might look like for the `purple_line()` function. Encourage them to think through the steps the computer needs to follow.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Ask for a few students to share an idea of their pseudocode. Then click to reveal the two example versions — one using repeated steps, one using a loop.\n\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use this opportunity to reinforce why loops are helpful. Ask students which version is easier to read or change later — and which one they’d prefer to debug.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0abe1eb7-3e7f-4288-9d0c-8ebc0f028f87",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5c817be-275f-4e82-9148-4e3fbab7008e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c0a763f9-1234-4e2c-9ca9-874740f29251",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now it’s your turn to decompose an image. You and your partner will choose one of the pixel images and break it down into patterns and functions — just like we practiced and then go code the image using your planned pseudocode.",
        "name": "Decomposing a Pixel Image",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c0a763f9-1234-4e2c-9ca9-874740f29251",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5c817be-275f-4e82-9148-4e3fbab7008e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3fbd6065-7feb-48a0-b134-3bc605358668",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Put students into groups of two. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair of students a copy of the Decomposing a Pixel Image activity guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Walk students through the tasks in their activity guide. Explain that they will first choose a pixel image to recreate, then identify patterns and define functions to break the image into smaller, manageable pieces. Next, they will write pseudocode to describe how they will code the image before sharing their plan with another group for T.A.G. feedback (Tell, Ask, Give). Encourage students to focus on decomposition and efficiency as they plan. Leave this slide up while students work so they can refer back to the steps.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The images are presented in order from easiest (top left) to most difficult (bottom right). If students are struggling to pick an image to discuss with their partner, consider guiding them to choose an image based on difficulty-level. \n\nEncourage students to refer back to UMPIRE as they work through today’s challenge.\n\nIf students struggle to get started and/or to visualize the shapes that make up the larger picture, consider sharing a copy of the **Digital Manipulative Support - Decomposing a Pixel Image** resource with them which should provide support for these students and allow them to get unstuck.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3fbd6065-7feb-48a0-b134-3bc605358668",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5c817be-275f-4e82-9148-4e3fbab7008e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "efd87425-4817-423c-a85c-f260118604a6",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "efd87425-4817-423c-a85c-f260118604a6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5c817be-275f-4e82-9148-4e3fbab7008e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9ee0c3f1-be06-4944-adbf-d488e5427dae",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Display the visual for the TAG feedback protocol. Remind them that their job is to Tell the group something they like about their code, Ask a question about the code, and Give a suggestion for improvement. Encourage them to focus on clarity, efficiency, and organization in the pseudocode.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students aren’t expected to finish coding their entire image in the allotted time. Encourage them to do the TAG protocol even if they have only just started coding. This will give them a valuable opportunity to receive feedback from peers and articulate their next steps for coding their projects."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9ee0c3f1-be06-4944-adbf-d488e5427dae",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5c817be-275f-4e82-9148-4e3fbab7008e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f257ade1-ced8-4bc8-a802-50d5ef356857",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f257ade1-ced8-4bc8-a802-50d5ef356857",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5c817be-275f-4e82-9148-4e3fbab7008e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "50d8a59b-c688-4f26-9311-2fe8a724896e",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Have students take out their Programming Fundamentals Unit Guide.\n\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that in this activity, the focus is on designing algorithms to recreate a pixel image, rather than collecting paint. Since the exact amount of paint needed is unknown, there are no paint buckets in this level. Instead, students will use `painter.set_paint(amount)` to set the amount of paint directly in their programs, ensuring they have enough to complete their image efficiently.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 11, Level 1 to convert their pseudocode into Python and create their pixel image.",
        "progression_name": "My Pixel Image"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "50d8a59b-c688-4f26-9311-2fe8a724896e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5c817be-275f-4e82-9148-4e3fbab7008e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0f3e3960-2ff4-4c75-bbcc-29b851f3774a",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As students work, check that they are defining and calling functions correctly and using consistent function names. Listen for debugging discussions and prompt students to compare their code to their pseudocode when they get stuck. Encourage them to test in small steps instead of writing everything at once.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Depending on the timing of the lesson, you can allot more time for students to finish coding their pixel images or allow them to click “Remix” on the level to create additional images.\n\nIf students struggle with debugging, ask guiding questions like, “What part of your code is working? What’s not?” or “How does this compare to your pseudocode?” Encourage them to use print statements to check their logic and troubleshoot errors."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The activity guide and Level 1 can be used to formatively assess the lesson objectives:\n- Breaking down a complex problem into smaller, manageable parts using decomposition\n- Writing and revising pseudocode based on peer feedback before coding their image\n- Defining and calling functions to code an image"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0f3e3960-2ff4-4c75-bbcc-29b851f3774a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5c817be-275f-4e82-9148-4e3fbab7008e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1235771e-693f-418b-a91c-61640d4d1efb",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Student Survey"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1235771e-693f-418b-a91c-61640d4d1efb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5c817be-275f-4e82-9148-4e3fbab7008e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "33c144b7-7597-44ea-add8-c12fab5f3949",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the learning objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students answer today’s Question of the Day by ranking themselves on the scales in their Unit Guide. Encourage them to reflect on their approach to problem-solving, collaboration, and focus while coding their pixel image.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Check in with students who seem unsure how to rank themselves. Ask guiding questions like, \"Did you follow a structured plan or experiment with new ideas?\" or \"Did you work through challenges independently or with a partner?\" Encourage them to use the scale to self-assess their coding process.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Have students reference specific functions they created in their programs when justifying their rankings. If time allows, ask a few students to share how their choices helped them break down and code the image efficiently."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The question of the day responses in the unit guide provide insight into how well students understand decomposition and their ability to apply it effectively in coding."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "33c144b7-7597-44ea-add8-c12fab5f3949",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5d7a5c9f-f2fd-4753-8497-37df17313b2e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d0075db5-b22b-4018-a1c5-9990ae574b94",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d0075db5-b22b-4018-a1c5-9990ae574b94",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5d7a5c9f-f2fd-4753-8497-37df17313b2e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "46e675e5-abbd-42c4-82e9-889a4107a492",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students pair up and share how they rated themselves on the scales in their Unit Guide. Encourage them to discuss which characteristic helped them the most and whether their approach was different from their partner’s.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Listen for students discussing how their problem-solving, collaboration, or focus impacted their coding process. Encourage them to provide specific examples from their work. If students struggle to compare approaches, ask guiding questions like, “Did you focus more on structure or creativity?” or “How did working independently or collaboratively affect your efficiency?”",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to reflect on how different approaches can be equally effective in problem-solving. If time allows, invite a few pairs to share their insights with the class to highlight the variety of approaches used."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "46e675e5-abbd-42c4-82e9-889a4107a492",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5d7a5c9f-f2fd-4753-8497-37df17313b2e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "88b5a390-9f65-4bea-bdb1-a2d7fb97c477",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What should the person do if the homework is not finished?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize that when a condition is not true, something different can (and should) happen. They may say things like:\n- \"Do the homework first.\"\n- \"Set a timer and start working.\"\n- \"No Netflix until it's done.\"",
        "name": "What Happens If Not?",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to think in everyday terms. What makes sense in their own lives?\n\nIf students struggle, try rephrasing with a simpler prompt like \"If I can't watch Netflix yet, what should I do instead?\""
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "88b5a390-9f65-4bea-bdb1-a2d7fb97c477",
        "lesson_activity.key": "03caf5d1-103e-421f-83e4-91e4ae31d742"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a11e6fdb-3ecb-409b-a1ee-f34d84675944",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a11e6fdb-3ecb-409b-a1ee-f34d84675944",
        "lesson_activity.key": "03caf5d1-103e-421f-83e4-91e4ae31d742"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "854df642-a450-4af0-b71e-e1f58281665a",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "854df642-a450-4af0-b71e-e1f58281665a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "03caf5d1-103e-421f-83e4-91e4ae31d742"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c5b08e21-d2ae-418e-b49e-bc7b63f6be1c",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the purpose and syntax of an `if` statement.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Two-Way Selection",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students need a refresher, ask \"What might happen if the `Painter` can't move south in this code? Will anything be painted?\""
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c5b08e21-d2ae-418e-b49e-bc7b63f6be1c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2ad50740-824e-4a8c-bca8-3c874d1886bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ac68d17f-8e7a-421e-b531-3899bf48d344",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What happens when the condition isn't true?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recall that when the condition is false, the program does nothing – it skips over the if block entirely."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ac68d17f-8e7a-421e-b531-3899bf48d344",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2ad50740-824e-4a8c-bca8-3c874d1886bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "346e43b7-7887-4851-8d67-1ebc1dcf4aed",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Have students take out their Programming Fundamentals Unit Guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define two-way selection."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "346e43b7-7887-4851-8d67-1ebc1dcf4aed",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2ad50740-824e-4a8c-bca8-3c874d1886bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d88698e6-ddbc-4a7b-98dd-3ccf94ae0f85",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Recall the syntax of an `if` statement."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d88698e6-ddbc-4a7b-98dd-3ccf94ae0f85",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2ad50740-824e-4a8c-bca8-3c874d1886bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "28454487-57de-4eff-87ae-4f21c95f802e",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We already know how this part works. The `Painter` checks whether it's on a bucket. If that's true, it takes the paint. This part is a one-way selection – something happens only if the condition is true.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "28454487-57de-4eff-87ae-4f21c95f802e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2ad50740-824e-4a8c-bca8-3c874d1886bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "62674c84-b21a-449e-8315-ca63db3773b1",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the `else` statement. Emphasize that the else gives the program a second path – something to do if the `if` is skipped."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "62674c84-b21a-449e-8315-ca63db3773b1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2ad50740-824e-4a8c-bca8-3c874d1886bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8086afff-a076-4373-b199-1e638a8833ce",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now we're adding something new: the keyword `else`. This tells the program \"If the condition is false, do this instead.\"",
        "remarks": true,
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Compare it to a real-life example (e.g., \"If I finish my homework, I'll go outside. Else, I’ll stay in and work.\")"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8086afff-a076-4373-b199-1e638a8833ce",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2ad50740-824e-4a8c-bca8-3c874d1886bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "58b1b088-2326-4ea1-99cb-04401daf7dea",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "58b1b088-2326-4ea1-99cb-04401daf7dea",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2ad50740-824e-4a8c-bca8-3c874d1886bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2ec20c1e-fe99-475c-b4eb-5a4ed3f66fab",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Emphasize how only one branch of the `if/else` will run."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2ec20c1e-fe99-475c-b4eb-5a4ed3f66fab",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2ad50740-824e-4a8c-bca8-3c874d1886bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6705a10d-6b3c-4b8c-9283-47d848c56d07",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "This is the `else` block. The program only runs this line if the `Painter` is not on a bucket. If the condition is false, it skips the `if` block and runs the `else` block instead.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6705a10d-6b3c-4b8c-9283-47d848c56d07",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2ad50740-824e-4a8c-bca8-3c874d1886bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3ae0d088-f934-4819-ac92-d6580f057a88",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Remind students that the code needs to be indented just like with functions, `while` loops, and `if` statements."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3ae0d088-f934-4819-ac92-d6580f057a88",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2ad50740-824e-4a8c-bca8-3c874d1886bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4c09ff30-ec49-4d70-9294-cdb8f66e9035",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Just like with `if` statements, the `else` block also needs to be indented. That tells the computer what belongs to that branch of the code.",
        "remarks": true,
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students struggle with indentation, ask \"What would happen if `marie.move()` wasn't indented here?\""
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4c09ff30-ec49-4d70-9294-cdb8f66e9035",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2ad50740-824e-4a8c-bca8-3c874d1886bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4d5e4494-ffdc-41c0-9d13-0d1dea18db30",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4d5e4494-ffdc-41c0-9d13-0d1dea18db30",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2ad50740-824e-4a8c-bca8-3c874d1886bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "dd9662be-eea1-4b2c-8dbc-775dc9819142",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 12, Level 1 to complete Levels 1 through 4.\n- **Level #1:** In Python Lab, students predict what the `Painter` will do before running it.\n- **Level #2:** Students complete a choice level where they are given a `Painter` program that only uses an `if` and they need to add an `else` to handle the opposite case.\n- **Level #3:** Students are given a buggy `Painter` program that always does the wrong thing when the `if` condition is false.\n- **Level #4:** Students complete a Check Your Understanding.",
        "progression_name": "if/else Statements"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "dd9662be-eea1-4b2c-8dbc-775dc9819142",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2ad50740-824e-4a8c-bca8-3c874d1886bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7b1012c1-393b-45cd-8991-aeb0f7a5d0d9",
      "position": 15,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Check Your Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7b1012c1-393b-45cd-8991-aeb0f7a5d0d9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2ad50740-824e-4a8c-bca8-3c874d1886bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6249fb86-06df-401f-906e-e3e009461edf",
      "position": 16,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As students work through the levels, walk around the room to observe their code and reasoning. Look for students who are correctly writing both branches of the `if/else` structure and using proper indentation. Pay close attention to whether students understand which part of the code will run based on whether the condition is true or false, and offer support if you notice confusion about which branch is being executed.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Level 2 is a choice level. Encourage students to try at least one and challenge themselves."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6249fb86-06df-401f-906e-e3e009461edf",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2ad50740-824e-4a8c-bca8-3c874d1886bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "65ff8f5b-ed97-41d7-8184-b009a5e1a8fd",
      "position": 17,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "65ff8f5b-ed97-41d7-8184-b009a5e1a8fd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2ad50740-824e-4a8c-bca8-3c874d1886bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "15b87fb6-c768-48f6-9c08-b8b015e736e6",
      "position": 18,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What did you notice about how `if/else` behaves?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize that `if/else` allows the program to always run one of two blocks – either the `if` block when the condition is true, or the `else` block when it's false, but never both. They may also note that else gives the program a fallback action, and that indentation matters for both branches. Some students may notice how `if/else` behaves differently when placed inside a loop, especially when it runs repeatedly.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *When is it better to use `if/else` instead of just `if`?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should understand that `if/else` is helpful when two different outcomes are needed – one for when the condition is true, and one for when it's false.",
        "duration": "20",
        "name": "Painter Challenges"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "15b87fb6-c768-48f6-9c08-b8b015e736e6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2ad50740-824e-4a8c-bca8-3c874d1886bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0ac99af9-6dda-48f5-ab72-13626d538b1c",
      "position": 19,
      "properties": {
        "description": "You've seen that `if` statements only run code when a condition is true. But `if/else` gives us a way to always make a decision—this or that, yes or no. It's useful when we want to make sure something happens either way.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0ac99af9-6dda-48f5-ab72-13626d538b1c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2ad50740-824e-4a8c-bca8-3c874d1886bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "77c91732-739e-48f9-9e56-e2b2306e6e85",
      "position": 20,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 12, Level 5 to complete Levels 5 through 8.\n- **Level #5:** Students complete a choice level where they use an `if/else` statement.\n- **Level #6:** Students complete a choice level where they use an `if/else` statement inside a `while` loop.\n- **Level #7:** Students complete a vocabulary Check Your Understanding.\n- **Level #8:** Students complete a Check Your Understanding."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "77c91732-739e-48f9-9e56-e2b2306e6e85",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2ad50740-824e-4a8c-bca8-3c874d1886bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "86bfc1b1-0fa3-46f6-b8d2-fa88ee095a66",
      "position": 21,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Solving Problems in The Neighborhood"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "86bfc1b1-0fa3-46f6-b8d2-fa88ee095a66",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2ad50740-824e-4a8c-bca8-3c874d1886bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bbd43529-8cec-4383-8059-04f267c5945f",
      "position": 22,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As students work, look for whether they are correctly using both branches of `if/else` and nesting it properly within a loop in Level 6. Watch for issues with indentation or logic that causes infinite loops or skipped code blocks.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Levels 5 and 6 are choice levels. Encourage students to try at least one and challenge themselves.\n\nThere is an optional activity guide available in the resource section for students to document their UMPIRE process as they work through today's coding challenges.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bbd43529-8cec-4383-8059-04f267c5945f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2ad50740-824e-4a8c-bca8-3c874d1886bc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "458f0b3a-3637-4f9a-bfb7-6fa84f9eaecb",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.",
        "name": "Question of the Day Reflection"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "458f0b3a-3637-4f9a-bfb7-6fa84f9eaecb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4b0e8bee-a067-4785-bfa8-0589565a2105"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "37257008-3780-4192-8ce4-cf810409eae6",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Pixels of Me Project Planning Guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students use the first box in their Planning Guide to brainstorm hobbies or interests they have and any careers that might be associated with them. Allow students to share their lists, idea webs, or sketches with an elbow partner as this may give them more ideas that they had not thought of themselves.  ",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Warm Up",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to come up with some hobbies they have both in and outside of school. The more they come up with, the more ideas they will have to choose from for their project pixel design. You can also prompt students to think about how their interests relate to their future career goals."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "37257008-3780-4192-8ce4-cf810409eae6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "52dd67a1-d716-4859-8615-14ae9374b980"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c9655808-faa1-491c-ad81-e762c97e374b",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c9655808-faa1-491c-ad81-e762c97e374b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "52dd67a1-d716-4859-8615-14ae9374b980"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "91ce66cd-8aa7-4918-a86a-1b1b478a178f",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students use the second box in their Planning Guide to brainstorm ideas for how they could represent any their ideas or interests visually. Again, allow students to share their ideas with a partner as this might give them more ideas beyond than what they had thought of themselves.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What skills have you learned in this unit that could help you create this pixel image?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should be able to explain how they can use the Neighborhood grid, Painter object and Python code such as functions, loops, and conditionals to “paint” their image. They should also explain how they can use computational thinking skills (decomposition, pattern recognition, abstraction, and algorithms) as well as skills and characteristics such as creativity, problem-solving, team work, detail-oriented, and others discussed throughout the unit to create their algorithms.  "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "91ce66cd-8aa7-4918-a86a-1b1b478a178f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "52dd67a1-d716-4859-8615-14ae9374b980"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4a51ead4-9d44-4210-8575-1d50e521c11a",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the first part of the project requirements.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the remaining project requirements.",
        "duration": "30",
        "name": "Activity",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Discussing the Project Requirements is part of the **Understand** step of the UMPIRE strategy. It helps students ensure they have a strong foundation from which to make their plan. \n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4a51ead4-9d44-4210-8575-1d50e521c11a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "52dd67a1-d716-4859-8615-14ae9374b980"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "06df1477-45c0-4241-82b4-df68aa3cf969",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to read the rubric on the last two pages of the project planning guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What do you notice about the project requirements and rubric? What does success look like for this project?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students share what they notice about the project requirements and rubric and identify the components to implement in their program.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What barriers do you anticipate to achieving success on this project?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students identify barriers they anticipate and share any questions they have about the project.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Hold That Thought strategy to allow students to write down their thoughts on paper first. Emphasize that they do not need to write complete sentences – they can write a few words, bullet points, draw a quick sketch, or anything else that will help them gather and recall their thoughts when it is time to share with the class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "06df1477-45c0-4241-82b4-df68aa3cf969",
        "lesson_activity.key": "52dd67a1-d716-4859-8615-14ae9374b980"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c05d663e-ff1b-4a40-a354-3d7889967b71",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the tasks students should complete on Day 1 to complete the project:\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the tasks students should complete on Day 2 to complete the project:\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the tasks students should complete on Day 3 to complete the project:\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Inform students that they will have the AI Chatbot on Level 2 to use for whatever support they need throughout the process. They can use AI to help them brainstorm, decompose their image, write pseudocode, or help debug any errors.\n\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to refer back to UMPIRE as they work through the project. Remind students that the AI chatbot can be used to help them **Make a plan** (brainstorming, decomposing, writing pseudocode, etc) as well as the **Inspect** step to get feedback and the Refine step to iterate and improve their program. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c05d663e-ff1b-4a40-a354-3d7889967b71",
        "lesson_activity.key": "52dd67a1-d716-4859-8615-14ae9374b980"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c91eb608-87fc-4fed-8206-bc020030de96",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to sketch their pixels of me design, identify the repeated patterns in the image, the functions they should define to create those patterns, and write pseudocode for their functions to plan their project on the Pixels of Me Planning Guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Help students who might be struggling with any of the decomposition steps or with writing their pseudocode for their functions. Encourage students to use the AI chatbot if they need help getting started.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Emphasize that the Pixels of Me design should be simple enough to create in the given timeframe while being complex enough to utilize the methods, user-defined functions with loops and conditionals. Students can use the AI chatbot to help them brainstorm different ideas for images they might use to represent their interests."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c91eb608-87fc-4fed-8206-bc020030de96",
        "lesson_activity.key": "52dd67a1-d716-4859-8615-14ae9374b980"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b1f55bf4-817c-422e-ab8c-bd50bfa7a2f4",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 13, Level 1 to select the corresponding grid size that they selected in their project planning guide.",
        "progression_name": "Pixels of Me Project"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b1f55bf4-817c-422e-ab8c-bd50bfa7a2f4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "52dd67a1-d716-4859-8615-14ae9374b980"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9449440e-62e1-4fb3-b939-ada080911da5",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Ensure students are on task. Encourage students to share and discuss their functions with a thought partner while working. As you move around the room, engage students with questions about their image, its repeated parts, the functions they plan on creating, and how they might use the AI chatbot.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Writing the code in this level is reflective of the **Produce** step of the UMPIRE strategy. \n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
